Commentary.Commentary: Right-o. The Aussie pace attack is in a discussion. Yes, just the pace attack. Who bowls how many overs? They might get 5 overs at best and Shane Warne jokes on air - 'All England can achieve in this 20 minutes is get out', that is if they aim too big. Just keep your shots in the bag, unless the bowling is too loose. Out come the English openers - Haseeb Hameed and Zak Crawley. Pat Cummins to start off to Hameed. Three slips, a gully and a man under the lid at short leg waiting. All the best.
... SECOND INNINGS ...
Forget the score, look at the time. 20 minutes left. Can England have both their openers batting when the first ball is bowled on Friday? They will certainly hope so. Please stay tuned.

Take your caps off for Jimmy, Stewy and Wood. The three seamers bowled their hearts out, with Broad taking a 5-fer and Anderson keeping it tight, while Hood's hostility kept Australia honest. But they could never really get wickets in clusters and that allowed the hosts to get away. Also, the tourists were without Ben Stokes with the ball post Lunch on Day 2, due to a side strain and that affected them too. Tough days.

End of a mighty innings for Australia. Built on small pieces of bricks laid by Warner, Harris and Labuschagne, the foundation was given strength by Usman Khawaja. His 137, which looked to be a struggle at first, but then turned out to be charismatic, pushed England on the back foot. He was given good company by Steven Smith, who made full merry of the loose stuff England bowled this morning, thereby allowing him to get away. And towards the end, as expected, the tail wagged. Now, if you do not like the word tail for Australia in this series, we do not blame you. They were 285/6 when Carey fell - they have finished on 416/8. Amazing.

And the innings ends with a bang! Cummins has played a fine gamble here. First, he made England think that the declaration is around the corner and then, when they felt that Australia will not declare, just surprised them, giving the openers roughly 20 minutes to survive for the day.

SIX! BOOM! That is out of here! Wow, what a shot by the spinner! Length ball, on off. Lyon rocks back, lines himself up and heaves it over the mid-wicket fence. Cummins has a big smile on his face as Australia declare on 416 for 8!
Length ball, on off. Lyon clubs it away past mid-wicket for a couple.

Scratch the previous BBL update. Well, part of it. Rain has stopped in Geelong and Melbourne Renegades have elected to chase against Brisbane Heat. For a start, the Heat have players to play the game.
Oh ho! A mighty heave and a miss! Length ball, around middle. Lyon looks to send the ball sailing in the crowd behind the mid-wicket fence but misses.
FOUR! Nice Gary! A full ball, on off. Lyon clears his front leg and hits it over the bowler's head. The ball trickles as it reaches the fence.
Fuller, around off. Starc pushes it past covers for one.
A short ball, down the leg side. Starc doesn't even have to duck under it to let it sail over his head.
Now there is an indication. Alex Carey has got his keeping gloves on. That is the first sign of declaration. Or. The dressing room does not have enough confidence in Starc and the rest.

FOUR! Classy shot from Nathan Lyon and the 400 is up for Australia. Wood goes short again, around off but thsi one sits up nicely for the batter. Lyon hangs back and fetches it from outside off before pulling it in front of square. The ball races through mid-wicket and Lyon picks up a boundary.
Another short ball, around middle. Nathan Lyon hops and keeps it out on the leg side.
Short again, at the body. Starc goes on the back foot and works it past short fine leg for a single.
Short of a good length, around leg stump. Starc punches it off the back foot towards mid on.

BBL UPDATES - There are supposed to be two games tonight, with Melbourne Renegades taking on Hobart Hurricanes at 12.35 pm IST (0705 GMT), followed by the Perth Scorchers-Sydney Thunder clash at 3.45 pm IST (1015 GMT). However, there is some rain around in Geelong and the start of the first game has been delayed.
A pacy bumper at 144 kph. Mitchell Starc manages to duck under it as the ball flies over his head.
Back of a length, at the body. Starc keeps it down towards mid-wicket.
A length ball, around the off pole and this one shapes away a bit. Nathan Lyon has a poke at it but doesn't get his bat anywhere close to the ball. End of a successful over from Stuart Broad.
Perhaps this is the best thing for Australia. Get bowled out and remove the stress of declaration.
Here comes Nathan Lyon. It will be interesting to see the approach now. 9 and 10 in the middle - have fun?

OUT! BOWLED! A 5-wicket haul for Broad! He has bowled really well and deserves this. Would be fair to say that he is probably the only one who has looked like he would take wickets here. But what a knock by Usman Khawaja. A sensational ton that has put his team well on top now. Not easy to score runs rightaway after coming back in the side after a big gap but he has delivered for his team. He bowls it full, on off. Khawaja looks to punch it away but his feet are a bit lazy on this one. It takes the inside edge and the ball crashes into the stumps. He walks off to a well-deserved standing ovation from his home crowd.
Commentary.Howout: b Stuart Broad

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Top shot! A bit short, on off. Khawaja rocks back and pulls it to the mid-wicket fence.

Are Australia EVEN thinking of a declaration tonight? We just saw David Warner in warmup clothes, teasing his Indian T20 League opening partner, Jonny Bairstow, on the fielding mess in the last over. Plus, there is no movement in the Aussie dressing room. And now, with just 13 overs left for the day after this over, it seems like Cummins is happy to keep England on the field, waiting for the declaration and just accumulate as many runs as possible. Maybe - bat first, bat big?
Length, on the pads. Starc works it towards fine leg for one.
Length ball, angling across and left alone.
In the air, but safe! A bit of extra bounce as Broad bangs it in back of a length. Starc gets the leading edge but the ball loops up and drops short of gully.
Short of a length, on off. Blocked out yet again by Khawaja.
Fuller, on off. Blocked out.
Full, on the pads. Starc works it towards deep backward square leg for one. Jonny Bairstow cuts it off and gets a nice cheer from the crowd while walking back to his mark.
On a length, on off. Blocked out.
A sharp short one, on middle. Worked towards mid-wicket.
Wood cranks it at 147 kph, full and angling across off. Starc looks to punch it through covers but the ball goes past the outside edge. Wood has a wry smile on his face.
Nice and full, around off. Khawaja gets the outside edge towards gully.
Fuller and angling across off. Khawaja leaves it with ease.
Short of a length, on off. Blocked out by Khawaja again.
Length ball, on middle. Blocked out.
Length ball, on the pads. Tapped past mid on for one.
Fuller ball, on the pads. Khawaja works it past square leg for one.
Back of a length, around 145 kph and around off. Starc goes on the back foot and dabs it down towards backward point.
Shorter in length, around off and angling across. Mitchell Starc doesn't play at it.

It's just not Mark Wood's day! Another short ball at 147 kph, at the body. Starc looks to keep it down on the leg side but its just that bit of an extra bounce that surprises him. The ball hits Starc flush on the glove and pops up towards the vacant silly point region.

FOUR! What happened here? Attempted short ball from Wood, at the body. Starc hangs back and this one doesn't rise up much. Starc pulls it towards square leg where Jonny Bairstow just doesn't pick the ball and the ball goes past him into the fence.
A pacy short ball, over leg stump. Mitchell Starc ducks under it.
Full, around off. Starc leans into the drive and gets it past mid off for a couple.
Full and wide, Khawaja shoulders arms. End of a maiden over from James Anderson.
Shorter in length, a bit of width on offer. Khawaja doesn't play at it.
Anderson goes fuller this time, around off. Khawaja sets up for the extravagant cover drive but ends up just about pushing it towards the cover region.
Again it;s a bit shorter in length, around off. Usman Khawaja goes on the back foot and punches it towards cover.
Back of a length, outside off and Khawaja leaves it alone.
Nice and full, outside off. Khawaja leans into it and pushes it to cover.

Stuart Broad is back on. 26-5-81-4 so far. Last attempt to take a Michelle. But wait. There is a problem. The umpires have a word with Joe Root and inform him that Broad cannot bowl now. So it is back to Jimmy who continues.

DRINKS BREAK. Another hour of toil for England. Story of the Test. If they felt getting Warner as the first wicket was good, Labuschagne came next. If they felt Marnus was a great wicket, Smith stood in their way. And then, when they finally managed to dislodge Smith, now the lower order stands in their way. In all these, Usman Khawaja has played a gem of an innings, one which has been witnessed by his wife and kid in the stands. Everyone's eyes will be on Pat Cummins with every passing over, as to when will the declaration come. With 18 overs left for the day, one suspects Pat is eyeing maybe another 3 overs or 400 - whichever comes first.
Fuller, on off. Pushed to mid off.
Bouncer down the leg side. Starc goes for the pull again but misses.
Short of a length, on middle. Turned to mid-wicket.

NOT OUT! Tell you what, my heart goes out to Wood. He bowls with everything that he has and creates chances but doesn't get the luck going his way. Short, on the body. Starc goes for the pull but misses. There is a sound as the ball goes past him and up goes the finger! But Starc reviews it straightaway. UltraEdge shows that the ball brushed the arm guard and not the gloves!

Mitchell Starc knew it straightaway and hence reviewed it without even thinking twice. The third umpire first checks the Hotspot and deems that there is a mark near the arm guard. He then moves on to UltraEdge to be sure and UltraEdge confirms that the ball just missed the glove and came off the arm guard. Good review from Starc and he extends his stay at the crease. The onfield decision is overturned to NOT OUT.

FOUR! Unlucky for Wood! A sharp short one, on the body. Starc is taken aback by the bounce and looks to leave it. But the ball hits the gloves and goes over the keeper. Boundary. That also brings up the 50-run stand between these two.
Length ball, angling across off. Left alone.
Yet another comfortable leave by Khawaja to end the over.
A touch fuller and closer to the stumps but wide enough for Khawaja to leave it.
A touch wider again and Khawaja won't chase it. They are not in a hurry at this point.
Short of a length, outside off. Khawaja lets Buttler collect this.
Fuller, on off. Khawaja drives it nicely to mid off.

Warne adds further on and compares Green to England's Andrew Flintoff. Shane says that initially, Flintoff used to struggle in his career with the bat because he perhaps went too much into defensive mode. But then, one fine day, Freddie decided to cut all hell loose and went on an all-out attack against the bowlers. Warne reckons that is a more positive approach and will help Green in the long run, given that he is only 22.
On a length, outside off. Left alone by Khawaja.
Wood fires a full one, on the pads. Starc clips it to the leg side.
Fuller ball, around off. Blocked out.
This is a sharp bouncer. On off but Starc sways away and Buttler leaps up and catches it.
A bit closer to the off pole and fuller. Blocked out with ease.
Length ball, on off. Starc blocks it from the crease.
Short of a length, outside off. Left alone.
Mark Wood (21.1-5-60-1) is back on.

Interesting thoughts from Shane Warne on air. He first admits, that the whole nation loves Cameron Green and the way he bowls. And he also remembers Green's 84 against India last summer, at the SCG. However, Warney is a touch worried about his batting and feels that perhaps, his current batting position is preventing him to play freely. Because he is coming in at 6, maybe, Green's initial instinct is to survive and then try to play shots, which is causing a muddle in his mind. Shane suggests that a slight shuffle might help Green, by allowing Carey to bat above him. And then, Green, Cummins and Starc at 7, 8 and 9 could be a deadly lower order. Worth a try.
Almost chopped on! Short ball, on off. Khawaja gets the inside edge as he looks to pull. The ball goes past the stumps and Buttler makes a good diving stop.
Fuller, around off. Khawaja drives it nicely through covers for a couple.
Short of a length, on the body. Starc clips it to fine leg for a single.
Length, on the pads. Starc works it to mid-wicket.
On the pads and Khawaja flicks it away for a single.
Length ball, on off. Blocked out.
On off, Khwaja presses forward to defend.
A loopy delivery now, on the stumps. Khawaja waits for it and pushes it down the ground for one.
FOUR! You can't bowl there to a batsman who has been out there for son long. Dragged down, on the pads. Usman Khawaja shuffles a bit and pulls it through square keg and into the fence.
Nicely flighted, outside off. Mitchell Starc caresses it through covers for a single.
Tossed up, around off. Starc strides forward and keeps it out on the off side.
Angled into middle and leg, Khawaja flicks it through square leg for a single.
Length, outside off. Starc taps it towards the slip cordon.
The Australian camp is seen choosing the ball that they will bowl with. But Lyon is still padded up and Warner is not wearing his whites yet.
Back of a length, around off. Blocked out by Starc.
On a length, on middle. Worked past mid-wicket for one.
Short of a length, on off. Blocked out.
On a length, around off. Blocked out by Khawaja.
Length ball, on off. Blocked out past cover for one.

Mark Howard on air pays a massive amount of tribute to Usman Khawaja. For those who don't know, Khawaja's country of birth is Pakistan. Howard states that if Khawaja had made even 10 percent of these runs for the country of his birth, he would have become a legend in Pakistan. To this, Shane Warne agrees. He says that in spite of this knock, Uzzie knows that his position in the team is not fixed. Warney admits that coming into this Test, Marcus Harris would have been replaced but Head's Covid case allowed him to carry on. And now, given the two half centuries, if Head does return for the last Test, Khawaja will be the one axed. The best thing is, adds Howard, is that Uzzie knows it, still, gives his best. Legend.
Flatter, on middle. Blocked out.
Darted on the pads. Starc clips it towards fine leg for three runs as the fielder chases it down.
Full, on off. Blocked out nicely.
Tossed up, on off. Starc blocks it out.
Fuller, on off. Khawaja drives it to deep cover for one.
Fuller, around off. Pushed down to mid off.
Short of a good length, outside off. Khawaja stands tall and eases it through cover-point for one.
Broad angles in a length ball from 'round the wicket and tries to attack the pads. Starc works it through mid-wicket for a single.
A length ball, outside off and left alone by Starc.
Around the top of off stump, Starc pushes it out on the off side.

In the air...safe! Now Mitchell Starc looks to take on Broad. Shortish ball, around off. Starc throws the kitchen sink at it as he looks to go downtown. The ball goes off the top edge and flies over the vacant cover region. They take a couple.

Khawaja is seeing it like a football out there. A length ball, on leg stump. Usman Khawaja stands tall and punches it on the up, right back past the bowler. The fielder from mid on gives chase and cuts it off. The batters get yet another three.
Leach comes from 'round the wicket and bowls it on the pads. Starc nudges it out.
On off, Starc defends it off the front foot on the off side.

Usman Khawaja is bringing out the variety now. Leach goes fuller, on off. Khawaja plays the reverse sweep and gets it behind point. The ball is racing into the fence but once again it is cut off. They get three.
Another round of applause from the crowd as Usman Khawaja crosses 3000 Test runs. On off, this is pushed nicely through covers for a couple.
Flatter delivery, around middle and blocked out.

Edged away! Leach tosses one up, outside off. Mitchell Starc presses forward and looks to drive it through covers but gets a thick outside edge which flies past first slip. Joe Root gives the chase and cuts it off before the ball ends up in the third man fence. The batters comes back for the third with ease.
On a good length, 138 kph and around middle. Usman Khawaja hops on the back foot to defend it out.
Broad digs in a short ball, at the body. Starc mistimes the pull shot towards mid-wicket but does get the single.

DRAMA! Broad has appealed for a caught behind but umpire Rod Tucker has shaken his head. With 1 second left on the clock, Root has reviewed. Well, nothing on the UltraEdge. The ball has missed the bat. But could this be LBW? It has hit Starc above the knee roll. UMPIRE'S CALL ON HITTING THE WICKETS! Wow. Nearly a 5-fer for Broady. A length ball, around off, Mitchell Starc looked to play the same shot as he did on the previous ball, straight back down the ground. But he missed and the ball went off something to Buttler. Now, there was a faint noise and Buttler made a small sign of appealing but was not too sure. Broad was sure, as always and Root too, from first slip, seemed convinced that there was a sound. They took the review and at that time, Broad snubbed Starc, 'Didn't you hit that? I heard a noise for sure.' Now, the first replay clearly showed the bat away from the ball but Shane Warne on air reckoned that could be LBW. And dear me, Warney was not entirely wrong! England retain their review as another positive in all this drama.
FOUR! Top-quality shot! Broad goes fuller this time and looks to clean Starc up. Starc though leans into the straight drive and times it perfectly past the bowler for a boundary.
Good-length ball, over off stump. Mitchell Starc makes a well-judged leave.

Just short! Stuart Broad is looking like the only one who might pick up a wicket here. Back of a length, around leg. Starc looks to turn it on the leg side but closes the face of the bat a bit early. The ball goes off the leading edge and falls short of Haseeb Hameed at short cover.

Another sort of half-volley, outside off from Jack Leach. Usman Khawaja leans into the cover drive and gets it through the infield. The ball is racing away into the fence but the fielder from deep point gets across to left quickly and keeps it down to two.
On a length, sliding into leg stump. Starc works it past mid-wicket for a single.
Angled into the pads, Khawaja works it through square leg for another easy single.
Khawaja comes down the track and pushes it back to the bowler.
Fuller, around off. Pushed to cover.
Tossed up, on middle. Mitchell Starc drives it down to long on for a single. Jack Leach is really struggling to find any rhythm out there.
Yet another length ball, around middle and leg this time. Khawaja defends it off the front foot.
Broad is attacking the stumps right now and keeps it around top of middle stump. Khawaja stays solid in defense.
Around middle, Khawaja blocks it out.
Right on the money from Broad! Length again, on top of off. Khawaja stands tall and punches it towards mid off.
LEG BYE! A length ball, on the pads. Starc looks to flick it away but misses. The ball comes off the thigh pad and rolls onto the leg side. The batters get an easy leg bye.
Short of a length, on leg stump. Usman Khawaja goes on the back foot and tucks it away towards backward square leg for one.
Leach gives it a bit more air and drifts it into off stump. Mitchell Starc strides out and pushes it away on the off side.
Around middle and leg, flicked away on the leg side for one.
This is sliding down the leg side and it is a bit short as well. Khawaja jabs it past backward square leg and gets back for another two.
Leach pulls back his length a bit and bowls it on off. Khawaja is pushed on the back foot to block it out.
Leach goes fuller and bowls it on off stump. Usman Khawaja presses forward and pushes it through the gap at extra cover. He picks up a couple.
Drifted into middle. Khawaja strides out and defends it back to the bowler.
A length ball, outside off. Mitchell Starc makes a leave.
Mitchell Starc is the next batter.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Stuart Broad has been bending his back in this over and does get his man in the end. Broad bangs in another short ball and it's just perfect. The ball is short enough to trouble the batter and is right at the body. Pat Cummins is taken aback by the steep bounce and tries to get out of the way but there's not much time for that. Jos Buttler leaps high once again and takes it well over his head. The visitors think the ball came off the glove but the umpire shakes his head. It is reviewed and UltraEdge shows that the ball just flicked the glove and the decision is reversed. Pat Cummins has to depart but he has done a decent job.
Commentary.Howout: c Jos Buttler b Stuart Broad

Commentary.Commentary: Joe Root signals the 'T' and England have reviewed this for caught behind. There could be some glove on that. There is a spike on UltraEdge and looks like the spike comes after the ball goes past the gloves. The TV umpire believes that this is conclusive evidence to overturn the decision.
Slightly fuller this time, around off. Cummins looks to drive it through covers but gets it off the inner half of the bat towards mid on.
Another short one, outside off. This time Cummins is able to leave it alone. Buttler does well to leap up and pouch it.

Nicely bowled! Stuart Broad is really steaming in and putting in an effort at the moment. Angles in a short ball, at the body. Pat Cummins looks to get his head out of the way but ends up getting hit on the arm. That must have stung.
Back of a length, around the off pole. Pat Cummins hangs back and keeps it down towards backward point.
A single as this is pushed to long off.
Loopy ball, on the pads. Cummins blocks it.
Flatter, on off. Khawaja gets the outside edge past point for one.
Similar line and length. Khawaja blocks it from the crease.
Tossed up, on middle. Khawaja taps it to the leg side.
Flatter, around off. Blocked out.
Who will bowl from the other end? It is going to be Jack Leach.
Length again, around middle. Cummins dabs it down on the leg side.
On a good length, around off. Left alone.

FOUR! Lucky! Broad tries to nip the ball in from outside off and does just that. Pat Cummins is caught in two minds on whether to play at it or not. He leaves his bat dangling till the last moment and finally looks to leave. The ball though goes off the edge and through the slip cordon. The ball races away into the third man fence and Broad is left frustrated.
Broad goes fuller this time and bowls it around off. Cummins drives it to wide mid off but can't get it through.

NOT OUT! Great comeback delivery from Stuart Broad. A length ball, around middle and nipping back in sharply. Pat Cummins goes back and across as he looks to block it out but misses. Cummins gets rapped on the pads and Broad is celebrating without even turning back. The umpire raises his finger and Cummins reviews it straightaway. Ball Tracker confirms that the ball was sliding down the leg side and it ends up being a great review by the skipper. Broad cannot believe it but the decision has been overturned.

Gone, is it? Yes, the umpire raises his finger to an LBW appeal against Cummins but the Aussie skipper reviews it immediately. The inside edge is checked but the UltraEdge shows nothing, barring a small spike when the ball goes past the bat. But no, no inside edge. Now comes the main part. An umpire's call would be enough for England to make the decision stick. MISSING LEG STUMP! Looking at the replays, that did seem to be heading down leg but in quick and live action, that might have looked out. The disappointment continues for England.

FOUR! Well, that's aggressive from the skipper. A loosener to start with from Stuart Broad as he bowls a half-volley, outside off. Pat Cummins leans in and creams it through covers for a boundary. Cracking start after the break.

The players are now back on the field. Just a small chat between the two batters and they are off. It will be the man with the bandana - not Dale Steyn - but STUART BROAD - to start off proceedings. Pat Cummins to face. Here we go...

Right. The moment has come and gone. The applause has been soaked in. Usman Khawaja takes a deep breath, closes his eyes and then walks out, followed by Pat Cummins. Mark Waugh on air believes that we are going to see carnage after Tea. But Michael Hussey disagrees and feels that this pitch is going to get harder and harder to bat on. There is a bit of cracking underneath the grass covering, so there is going to be plenty of inconsistent bounce. So Mr. Cricket wants Australia to bat deep and score as much as they can in the first innings, rather than try to score quick runs,
... DAY 2, FINAL SESSION ...

BHANUKA RAJAPAKSA RETIRES! In some shocking news which has come overnight, one of Sri Lanka's upcoming promising batters, Bhanuka Rajapaska, has decided to call it quits at the age of 30. The letter which he has written states family obligations. Cannot argue on that, but this is really sad for the Lankans. They have been trying to rebuild over the last 5 years and seem to have finally found a core, but this will be a setback. Rajapaksa was superb with the bat, especially exploring the off-side area inside out.

INTERNATIONAL CRICKET UPDATES - Meanwhile, what is happening elsewhere? We could be in for possibly a superb final day at The Wanderers, Johannesburg. The second Test between South Africa and India is tantalisingly poised, with the hosts needing 122 runs and the Indians needing 8 wickets. On a normal Day 4 pitch, this looks an easy win for the Proteas but this Jo'burg pitch, which has already started to show tricks from Day 3, could provide a lot of assistance to the visitors. Should be fun.

England are a bowler down with Stokes not bowling and the lack of real fast bowlers is hurting them. Only Mark Wood is bowling with venom from one end while the others are in the mid 130ks. They have done the hard work, taking 6 wickets and this pitch is still good enough for batting. So if they can restrict Australia to 370, they still have time to fight back. However, Australia have always been known for rearguard action and one man who has scored more runs in this series than almost all English batsmen, barring Root and Malan - Mitchell Starc - is yet to come. Australia will believe they have enough on the board and will go for the kill in all likellhood post Tea. Up the ante, score quick runs and declare with an hour left for Stumps or get bowled out, with the score touching 400. Can someone in the English camp avoid that happening? The final session starts at 10.30 am IST (0500 GMT). 34 overs left in the day.

Alex Carey was given a real working over by Mark Wood and he struggled a lot, making 13 from just 39 balls. But he spent crucial time at the crease, not giving his wicket away until that 39th ball, where he tried to go after Root. He was involved in a 43-run stand with Khawaja and that helped the hosts to recover. This innings has been the one for the comeback man, Usman Khawaja and let's accept - he has not been at his best. At least, till Smith got out. Once Smith fell, Khawaja seems to have come into his own and is looking deadly dangerous now.

Right. So what happened in the post-Lunch session? 33 overs were bowled in 150 minutes. Poor overrate again. 3 wickets were picked up, so that's some say. But a total of 112 runs were scored which has taken Australia to some sort of safety again. England struck the right chords post Lunch and managed to dismiss Steven Smith quickly. And then they had Australia 5 down, with the second new ball doing its trick. But as has been the case throughout the series, the visitors have been unable to maintain that pressure and the hosts got away.

The crowd just loves it. Small moments like these - getting to a hundred before a break, mean a lot to a player. And the supporters love it too. The day has not ended, nor has the match but for now, the SCG is soaking in the moment of return to Test cricket. Warner, who has played cricket with Khawaja since they were 10-year olds, is pumped up and pats him ferociously on the back. Cummins, like a graceful captain, allows Uzzie to go ahead first and stays out at the boundary, just so that the southpaw gets the moment to himself. Superb team spirit.
Loopy ball, on off. Blocked out. That is Tea on Day 2!
Shorter and outside off. Cummins goes for the cut but gets the outside edge to third man for three.

THERE IT IS! Usman Khawaja, the comeback king! His 9th Test ton and boy, he is pumped about it! Coming back in the side after 3 years and he has proved his worth! Off comes the helmet and he soaks in the massive applause from the crowd. His family is in the stands and it must be a special feeling for him. Stokes applauds him too, good sporting spirit by the big man. This has been a brilliant knock by him. Usman Khawaja was put under a bit of pressure late on Day 1 when the English bowlers had their tails up but he weathered that. Runs came freely after that and he deserves every bit of this applause. He gets to his ton by working this short ball towards deep square leg. Anderson's chase and dive cuts the ball off. But they get three runs.
Here we go! Shorter, on off. Cummins pushes it past covers for one. Usman Khawaja is on strike now. The crowd is getting in on it.
Full and on off. Cummins blocks it out.
Loopy ball, on off. Cummins blocks it out.
Jack Leach (19-2-62-0) is brought on for what will probably be the final over before Tea. The field has been brought in closer just to keep Cummins on strike.

BOOOOOOOOOOOOOO goes the crowd! Oh Patrick, why did you have to take the single on the last ball? But like a perfect teammate, Usman Khawaja smiles. Full, outside off, deliberately looped up, the skipper lunges and drives it beautifully. Extra cover makes no effort whatsoever in trying to stop the ball, conveniently giving the single. Oh... mind games, tell ya. England want Uzzie to stay on 99 at Tea.
FOUR! Again! Too full this time. Cummins clears his front leg and thumps it over mid on for a boundary.
FOUR! Smashed down the ground! Short and outside off. Cummins rocks back and hammers it down the ground for a boundary.

POSTPONED, POSTPONED, POSTPONED! No, not again. Another match in the Big Bash League gets pushed ahead due to Covid. Melbourne Stars were due to play Adelaide Strikers in Adelaide tomorrow but that has been postponed, with those members of the Melbourne Stars squad who recently contracted COVID-19 deemed PHYSICALLY AND MENTALLY UNFIT to play after being released from isolation. Having been forced to stay in up in hotel rooms for a week and with some players potentially still suffering the lingering effects of the virus, travelling to Adelaide and playing tomorrow night has been determined to be a bridge too far. While the Stars technically have a squad of players available to play the Strikers tomorrow night, the mental and physical toll of the past week has been significant. This is really, really sad. The Sixers and Strikers remain the ONLY TEAMS unaffected, with the Sydney Thunder, Hobart Hurricanes, Melbourne Renegades and Perth Scorchers having players unavailable at times this season.

WOMEN'S ASHES NEWS - Aha... the Women's one is coming sooner than expected. Quarantine requirements for the ODI World Cup in New Zealand has seen the women's Ashes schedule brought forward by a week. The Women's Ashes will now begin a week earlier than originally planned with three T20Is at the Adelaide Oval on January 20, 22 and 23 before the Test is played as scheduled at the Manuka Oval from January 27-30. Canberra will also play host to the first of three ODIs, a day-nighter on February 3, before the series is rounded out by the final two one-dayers at Melbourne's Junction Oval on February 6 and 8. These are being done to allow both teams to enter hotel quarantine in New Zealand ahead of the one-day World Cup, which begins from March 4, 2022. Both teams are set to play up to two warm-up games in the week leading into the event, and given the isolation requirements, are required to be in New Zealand by mid-February.

DRINKS! Buttler needs some medical attention after that blow on the previous delivery so the umpires have called for a Drinks break. Excellent discussion between Mark Howard and Isa Guha on air. Howard points out that Mark Wood is bowling tremendously and his extra speed is definitely causing worries to the Aussie batters. Howard adds that Jofra Archer is being missed sorely by England, given what he did at Lord's to Smith and Labuschagne. To this, Guha does agree but she also adds a valid point. Isa says that in the Big Bash League alone, she has seen as many 15 Aussie bowlers who can bowl more than 150-plus. But back in England, this is very rare, as the pitches and conditions support bowlers who can bowl up to 130 kph. She says Wood is the fastest in the whole country but the fast bowling stocks are a bare minimum. She names a few, like Saqib Mahmood, whom she expects to play for England in all formats, then Tymal Mills, who is hit with injury, then George Garton perhaps, but overall, there isn't much coming. Now Mark says that to beat Australia in Australia, you need pace in your stocks. He recounts how India beat them last year in their own backyard, through Jasprit Bumrah and Mohammed Shami. Here, poor Wood has to do everything himself, given that Stokes is also not bowling now and when you get 140-plus from one end but 130 from the other, it becomes easier for the batters. Also, this will take a toll on Wood though, if he has to single-handedly keep on bowling fast, with no support from the other end.

Welcome back. And we greet you with this update from England on Ben Stokes - Currently being treated for left side tightness. Will be assessed over the course of the next hour. Well, that effectively means he will not bowl for the rest of this day now. And it also means he will not be around for the first hour of this session on the field as well. Sigh. Problems compounding for England. Out come the two batters who have been unseparated since last evening, for around 36 overs now - Steven Smith and Usman Khawaja. The conditions are sunny but not entirely, with a dark cloud patch lurking around somewhere above. Root has his team in a huddle and English fans will hope that there is some uplift in the mood from here on.
... DAY 2, SESSION 2 ...

It is all in the mind. The opposition is 209/3, a bowler is nearly down and fielding has not been the greatest. 500 coming up? Well, if you want to believe and make it happen. But if you think positive and look at the batting beyond this pair, all you see is a soft underbelly which has been getting exposed for over an age now, by all teams. As the great Sir Geoff Boycott says - Always add two wickets to the current score and then look at the total. Makes a difference.' Definitely, sir. If 209/3 points to a possible 500, then 220/5 gets that down to 300 - simply because of the ever-lasting out-of-form middle order. What will England choose to believe? A glass half empty or a glass half full? They have got a few minutes to think before the second session, which is scheduled to start at 7.40 am IST (0210 GMT).

Well, England may not be competitive but that is not Australia's problem. They will look to make use of every opportunity that they get and Usman Khawaja will look to do just that. Smith, on the other hand, is back in the 50s zone after missing out in the previous two Tests and he will want to get a big one on his home ground. What can England do? How can they stop the Aussies?

The visitors started this morning with some very ordinary bowling, keeping the lengths too full. Runs started to come easily and then, they resorted to hit-the-deck bowling, around the bodyline. The tactic worked and the runs stopped coming by. And as is the case with modern day batsmen, there was a mistake and an edge was induced - only for skipper Joe Root to shell a sitter. And to compound his woes, his deputy, Ben Stokes, is off the field due to a back strain. Unless that back gets a good rubbing in this Lunch break, England are effectively a bowler down and we are not even done with a proper full day's play yet.

The story? More of the same for either side. Australia continue to get scoring balls, then are forced into submission, only to see a reprieve and eventually, the pressure being eased off. We struggled to get continuous cricket this morning because of the on-off drizzle. And such drizzles are more irritating, because they do not linger for long. And stoppages of 15-20 minutes hurt more, because you just get into a rhythm and it gets broken. So that was a challenge for the Aussies but England just do not seem to be mentally here.

And that brings an end to this start-stop, start-stop session. We have played for more than 150 minutes in terms of time but if you look at the session details - just 31.1 overs bowled. That too, happened because Leach and Malan bowled, which helped the over rate a touch. Perfect session for Australia, not losing a single wicket and scoring 83 runs.

This has been the problem with England throughout this series. A complete execution. Planning + persistence + execution = wanted result (9 out of 10 times). England have been planning every time. Many times, we see innovative fields as well, like we are seeing now. But half the time, they are not persistent enough. Like, we see some really stupendous bowling but that lasts for around 30 minutes. And another big problem is - if that persistency results in a chance, it is not taken. We keep saying bad luck to Jack Leach or some other bowler but you just cannot put lapses in concentration down to bad luck all the time. Yes, it is understandable that Root is under pressure but that is what experience is for. You have got to ride all the pressure and keep focussing on the game all the time.

So cannot have any more breaks now.

We are ready for play! The English players are seen in a huddle as the overnight batters, Steven Smith and Usman Khawaja make their way to the middle. Stuart Broad is ready to steam in and finish his incomplete over.

England were quite unhappy when Stumps were called early on Day 1 because they had a strong hour of play leading up to the close of play. They bowled in the right channels and did not allow the batters many opportunities to score easy runs. Now, England have been in such situations before when they have the Australian batters on the mat but then fail to finish things off. There is still a long way to go in this innings but it would be interesting to see if the visitors have learned from their mistakes in the series.

Hello and a very warm welcome to the second day of the fourth Ashes Test. We had plenty of rain on Day 1 and not even 47 overs were completed. But the forecast now is much better. Yes, there is rain expected but that the forecast for rain is late in the day so the first two sessions hopefully, should go smoothly. The first hour remains crucial for both the teams as if England manage to take a couple of wickets, they will have a firm group on the game here. What will happen? We will inform you as it happens.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

Right. That is all from Day 1 and this Test could be an exciting one if and that is a big IF the rain allows us to. We will be back for Day 2 on 6th January so do join us for the same. The day is scheduled to start at 4:30 am IST (11 pm GMT, previous day) but our buildup begins early so do join us for that. So do join us then!

The visitors might have lost the series but came out this morning playing for pride. The ball did swing around a bit at the start but the Aussie openers kept the English pacers at bay. Stuart Broad then got the wicket of David Warner for the 13th time in his career and this created an opening for England. But the rain returned and they could not build up the pressure. It was in the last hour of play that their seamers came to life. Anderson bowled a brilliant probing spell which brought the wicket of Harris. Wood was brought on in the following over and found the outside edge of Labuschagne's bat. They would now look to take a few quick wickets in the first hour of the second day and get a firm grip on the game.

So, a day filled with rain stoppages has finally come to an end. There was hardly any play in the first two sessions as less than 22 overs were bowled across those sessions. The hosts did get off to a good start as Warner and Harris brought up a 50-run stand. Warner then fell but Harris carried on and Marnus Labuschagne gave him ample support. The two top-order batters put Australia on top in the third session as another fifty partnership was brought up. It looked like these two would bat till the end and yet another day of Test cricket will be dominated by Australia. But that was not to be as the conditions then changed a bit and the ball started to move around more. Nelson brought some good fortune to England for a change and they took a couple of wickets in consecutive overs. The visitors tightened the screws and would have wanted to take at least one wicket before the close but that was not to be as the rain returned and brought down the curtains.

They want the game to go on for the remaining 30 minutes or so. But, that is not to be and Stumps have been called! The rain has gotten lighter to be honest, we perhaps could have had a few more overs here.

BIG BASH UPDATES - Let's start with a positive news. Tonight's Sixers-Heat fixture has been confirmed. However, we still do not know the availability of the squad for Brisbane! That is because players are still awaiting the results of the PCR tests conducted last night. This match was supposed to happen last night, remember? Meanwhile, a few international teams are in need of a Head Coach. After the departure of Mickey Arthur, the Sri Lanka team is currently looking for a new coach. They have appointed Rumesh Ratnayake, the former Sri Lankan pacer as the interim coach for their upcoming home series against Zimbabwe but the search for a permanent leader continues. The same goes for Afghanistan as they are looking for multiple coaches now. Not much to talk about Warner and Harris. They have both looked quite good in the middle. Warner hit a few nice boundaries whenever he got the opportunity to open his arms. As the game goes on, expect both these batters to score more freely. Especially once the ball gets old. For now, though, it is about defending the good deliveries and punishing the bad ones. Do join us at around 8 am IST (2:30 am GMT) for the second session if the rain permits.

A frustrating session for a couple of reasons. Firstly, the rain had us on our toes and saw players coming off a couple of times and secondly, because of how England bowled in this brief session. With a fair bit of cloud cover, it was expected that the pair of Anderson and Broad would make the batters dance to their tunes. They even found some help from the pitch but they were just not consistent with their lines. Anderson was the more accurate of the two and made the batters play a lot more than Broad. England would need to rethink their plans in this break.

We are off! The rain is back and off go the players. I suspect it will be that kind of a day. With about 10 minutes or so left for the scheduled Lunch break, the umpires have decided to take the break right away. A minimum of 10 minutes of play is required before the break, which isn't possible so, it's best to get done with the Lunch break at the earliest.

The importance of an opening stand in Tests cannot be overstated. If your openers do not do well, the middle order is exposed to the new ball and is put under a tremendous amount of pressure. The English side were blessed to have two champion players in recent time who were maestros when it came to opening an innings. Andrew Strauss and Sir Alaistar Cook would more often than not blunt the attack of the opposition to provide a solid base for the English middle order to work from. But since their retirement, the English lions have been toothless lions so to speak. If you look at their numbers in the last two years, you can see why this English side has struggled and why Joe Root has become a virtual opening batter on many occasions. In this period, England have used the joint second-most opening combinations after India in Tests and too much chopping and changing hasn't let a pair make the opening spot their on. They have played the maximum innings as well but their average is a lowly 26.07, which is better only than Afghanistan and West Indies. Interestingly, they have got 9 50+ stands in this period - tied only with India - but as the numbers suggest, they have been few and far in between. If England have to revive in the longest format of the game, they must identify a pair that will open for them for a long period of time and then back them to do good at the top. Otherwise, we shall witness the same story again and again where the main character, Joe Root, is left to save his team out of trouble.

England head into this Test match having already lost the series and to add to that, are going through a covid crisis as members of the coaching staff tested positive. Joe Root's captaincy has been under scrutiny as well but he has been the only one who has done his talking with the bat. None of the other English batters have been able to come up with an answer to the Aussie attack, well Dawid Malan has been somewhat successful but it just hasn't been enough. The visitors don't have that pressure of staying in the series anymore and their batters will look to come out and express themselves. Stuart Broad will come in for the injured Ollie Robinson and that's the only change they have made to the playing XI. So, the real question is, can England somehow manage to avoid the 5-0 defeat? Well, the weather might just help them in this match but they will need to step up their game as well.

The Aussies have been simply brilliant so far in the series and haven't really put a foot wrong under new skipper, Pat Cummins. The bowlers have been firing on all cylinders and the batters have been consistent as well. Talking about their bowling, what a brilliant debut Scott Boland had at his home ground and he will be looking to carry that confidence into this match as well. Travis Head is set to miss this Test due to covid and Usman Khawaja has been confirmed as his replacement in the playing XI as the rest of the team remains unchanged. This shows that the Aussies want to win every single game and don't want to bench any of their big guns. The hosts will look to continue their dominance and push for a 5-0 victory.

Hello and a very warm welcome to the 4th Ashes Test between Australia and England at the Sydney Cricket Ground. It is the Pink Test, which has become a regular feature of the Australian summer over the past few years. The hosts come into this one having sealed the series and will now have their eyes on a whitewash. England, on the other hand, will be desperate to avoid another defeat here. The weather forecast is that there's going to be a fair bit of rain around for the entirety of the match, so, let's keep our fingers crossed.
... MATCH DAY ...

So both the sides have made one change - England have brought in the veteran Stuart Broad in place of Ollie Robinson who is ruled out due to injury while Australia, as expected, replaced Travis Head with Usman Khawaja. Australia are still going with a balanced squad and not trying the bench with the likes of Mitchell Swepson who still awaits his Test debut. This says how much the host wants to dominate on the home pitch and against their arch-rivals.

We are back. Marcus Harris and David Warner are the openers! Ollie Pope is the keeper for the visitors as both Bairstow and Buttler have hurt their hand. James Anderson has the new ball in hand. Here we go...

Now Australia will just look to bat normally and post something which will ensure they can't lose the game. England on the other hand, need wickets and quickly. Will the fightback continue from them? We will find out.

The Australian bowlers could not capitalize when they had England completely on the backfoot! They were brilliant with the new ball but had no answers to the counter-attack from Bairstow and Stokes. However, they were really good this morning and have given their side a very good lead. Boland continues to impress as he finishes with a four-fer. All of them except for Labuschagne got a wicket at least but Boland was the pick.

Australia have made quick work of the three wickets they had to take this morning but England will be very delighted with their recovery! From 36 for 4, they have finished with a score close to 300 and given Australia a lead of 122. The visitors have just the one man to thank and that is Jonny Bairstow! He played an innings of a lifetime. First it was Stokes who took England to safer shores with a good stand and then Wood hung in there. Bairstow though was the mainstay, he did not add a lot on Day 4 but surely did his job and has kept England in the game.

Australia, their game plan will be quite simple, knock the remaining wickets quickly and then bat England out of the game. Can they do the first part successfully though? We will find out.

England needed a knock like that. They have shown close to no fight in the series so far and after the first session, it seemed the Aussies are on the verge of embarrassing them yet again but Bairstow has dug his side out of the grave. Yes, England are still behind in the game but that knock will give them belief and surely boost their morale big time.

Flashback - January 3, 2003. A certain Steven Rodger Waugh punched a ball from Richard Dawson through point to register a century on the last ball of the day - that too, in the Ashes, at the SCG - which had lifted a whole nation. 19 years later, a similar incident occurred, in the Ashes again, and at the SCG once more - this time by an Englishman. Only points of difference - Bairstow got it on the fourth ball of the final over and while Dawson was a spinner, Cummins is a fast bowler. Certain moments in sport are so tremendous that they leave you bedazzled for a lifetime. Waugh's was certainly one. Jonny matched that. And with that, we welcome you to the fourth day of the fourth Test of the Ashes, at the Sydney Cricket Ground. Ahhh... we still have got goosebumps from the previous evening!
... DAY 4, SESSION 1 ...

What does Day 4 bring us then? Excitement and anticipation. If Bairstow bats through the morning session, well, Australia will suddenly be on the back foot, because it then becomes a one-inning shootout. On the other hand, it is a new day and if Australia can finish things off in the first hour, they will still have a sizeable lead. One thing to remember is - this is Sydney. Which means, post Day 3, batting gets really difficult. So the cracks will definitely open up and that means Lyon could get purchase in the final innings. The first ball of the day is scheduled to be bowled at 4.30 am IST (2300 GMT, previous day), weather permitting, but the buildup will be done well in advance. So please, please, please - tune in early. ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

A nightmarish second half of the day for Australia? Ummm... perhaps. They did get rattled. They are still well ahead in this Test but the way England fought back from 36/4 is something which they did not expect. However, their main worry would be Scott Boland's injury. If they have to bowl with a bowler down in the second innings, it is going to be a problem as we witnessed on Day 3 too. The most surprising aspect was the way the English batsmen targetted Nathan Lyon - 12-0-71-1 - whoa! He did get Stokes but boy, he got a pounding from Stokes, Bairstow and even Wood!

A word now, on Jonny Bairstow. And also, a question to England's selectors, as to why was this bloke left out from the first two Tests? This is what he brings to the table. It is not just the runs but the way he gets them. And when you fight fire with fire, that is when you get entertainment. We all remember Ben Stokes' century in the 2014 Ashes. This was close to that, if not better. He first saw Stokes changing his batting style after that bowled reprieve and then he too, inducted some of that in him. And the result is - at the end of the day he is still fighting, on a 103 not out, from just 140 balls, with 8 fours and 3 sixes.

Australia bounced back, with two quick wickets, but then, they got a taste of their own medicine. Just like their tail has been wagging against England, this time it was the opposition to do so. Mark Wood hung around and boy, he did not just stand there. He decided to counter punch and that 72-run stand for the 7th wicket is what frustrated Australia. Bairstow got confidence in his partner and then reached his century as well, making it a day to remember for not just English fans, but for all cricket fans, in general.

A day of two halves, shall we say? Australia started as they always have in this series, putting the foot right on England's throat. Bang, bang, bang, bang - suddenly, England are 36/4 at Lunch. And again, memories of 68 all out start flooding. But then, something happens. Ben Stokes gets a slice of luck, being adjudged LBW, when he was actually bowled but the bails did not fall! The overturned decision saw the game change tremendously, with Bairstow and Stokes going on an all-out attack, reminding us of their partnership in the 2019 Ashes in Headingley. They added 128 for the 5th wicket, which pushed the Aussies on the back foot.

Before we delve into what happened in the day, here's Smith junior talking to the broadcasters. Jeez - Marnus Labuschagne. His pet name, you see. On England's fightback, Labuschagne says that they always knew that this was a good wicket and even though they took 4 quick wickets, they expected a fightback. Tells that this is the Ashes, which is always competitive. On Scott Boland, he does agree that seeing him in whites is a good sign but is not quite sure whether he would be able to bowl on Saturday as they need to assess him overnight.

Ahhh... what a glorious scene. The first thing that happens after that last ball is Aussie players coming across to congratulate Bairstow on his century. And it is not just one or two players. Almost the entire team gets across, which shows what a splendid innings this has been from him, in trying circumstances. And now, Australia themselves get into a huddle, probably telling themselves that okay, we have let an opportunity slip, but the match has not ended yet. However, what a day it has been.

Bairstow takes his helmet off and runs down the pitch in celebration. The entire SCG stands up in applause. Not only English fans, but even the Aussies have loved this knock. Superb to watch.

However, UltraEdge showed a spike when the ball went past the glove and then off the helmet to point. So the onfield decision got overruled and Wood looked surprised. The catch was taken by Lyon, by the way and the 72-run stand is broken.
