SIX! Third six already by Bairstow in this innings! On a length, on middle. Jonny Bairstow thumps it over square leg for a maximum.
Another short ball and Bairstow lets it through.
A short ball from Green, on middle. Bairstow sits under it.
This one nips back in, on a length, on off. Blocked out. Wicket-maiden for Cummins.
Length ball, outside off. Wood looks to pull but miscues it to cover. It came off the toe end of his bat.
Length and on middle. Wood punches it to mid on and looks for a quick single but is sent back.
Mark Wood is the new man in.

OUT! TAKEN! The skipper does it and Khawaja with a brilliant catch! Soft dismissal though and Buttler goes back on a duck! A length ball, on off. Jos Buttler is too early as he tries to block it. The ball tends to stick a bit and he chips it straight to short cover where Usman Khawaja holds onto it. A string of low scores for Jos Buttler.
Commentary.Howout: c Usman Khawaja b Pat Cummins

Commentary.Commentary: Length and on middle. Buttler hops and tucks it to short mid-wicket.
On a length, on middle. Buttler blocks it on the leg side.
Fuller ball, on middle, pushed to covers.
This is much quicker and Bairstow defends it out.
SIX! Pain, what pain for Jonny Bairstow! A full ball, on middle. Jonny Bairstow gets on his knee and slogs it all the way over backward square leg for a biggie.
Loopy ball, on off, pushed to covers.
Shorter and on off, punched to mid off.
Tossed up, on middle. Bairstow whacks it wide of deep square leg and collects a couple of runs.
Touch fuller, on off. Buttler blocks it out solidly.
Short of a length, on off. Buttler hops and taps it to point.
Length ball, outside off. Left alone.
Full ball, outside off, defended out.
A length ball, angling on middle, flicked to square leg.

Halt in play! Jonny Bairstow gets hit on the right thumb and the physio is out to have a check. He looks in some serious pain. Bairstow is taking some painkillers but that was a nasty hit for him. Some taping on it and looks like Bairstow will continue and he gets some applause from the crowd.

Over the slips! That will sting for sure! Length ball, lands on off and just takes off. Bairstow looks to block but gets pinged on the thumb of the bottom hand. He takes the single as the ball goes over the slips but he is in pain. He is in a lot of pain. He throws his bat down on the ground and goes down in pain.
Jos Buttler is the new man in.

OUT! LBW! Stokes knew as soon as it hit! He kept his head down and started walking straight to the dressing room! A flatter ball, angling on middle, this one skids through. Ben Stokes was deep in his crease and he tried to flick but misses and got rapped front on the pads. Lyon turned to appeal and the umpire had already raised his finger. A wonderful innings from Ben Stokes comes to an end. Helped his team to get in a good position. A relief for Nathan Lyon, he was going for runs but this will give him some boost. Good piece of bowling too. He fires it in, did not try to spin it at all, and beat Stokes with the pace.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Nathan Lyon

Commentary.Commentary: Slightly quicker, on middle. Jonny Bairstow works it to deep square leg for one.
A loopy ball, on middle, flicked on the leg side.
Flatter and on middle. Blocked out.
Darted on the pads, this is flicked to deep square leg for a couple.
SIX! HUGE! A tossed-up ball, on off. Jonny Bairstow slog-sweeps it high over mid-wicket for a biggie. Intent from England.
Full and wide outside off. Stokes looks to go over covers but gets the outside edge. The ball flies in the air wide of deep cover for a couple.
Length, on the pads. Worked towards fine leg for one. Suddenly, the Barmy Army is getting louder and louder.
Short ball, on middle. Jonny sits under it.
Fuller, on off. Pushed to mid on.
Length, on the pads. Tapped to mid-wicket.
Length, down the leg side. Bairstow misses the flick.
SIX! WOW! High and handsome! Tossed up, wide outside off. Stokes dances down the track and lifts it all the way over the cover fence. That is a shot and a half.
Full, on middle. Worked to long on for one and that brings up the fifty for Jonny Bairstow. He raises his bat to his mates and gets back to work.
Nicely tossed up, outside off. Jonny punches it to cover.
Flatter, around off. Pushed to cover.
A single as this is pushed to long on.
FOUR! Stokes seems to have decided that he will not let Lyon rule the roost! Tossed up, on off. He goes low and slog-sweeps it to the mid-wicket fence.
Aerial but safe! Full, on off. Stokes looks to drive it nicely but gets the outer half of the bat. The ball flies over cover and goes to deep point for one.
Fuller, angling across off. Left alone.
Play and a miss! This time Stokes stays up and looks to pull this short ball. But it goes past his bat. There are two men placed in the deep for that exact shot.
OUCH! That stays low! Short, on middle. Stokes gets low thinking that the ball will sail over him but it stays a bit low and hits him on the helmet.

Fuller, on off. Tapped to mid-wicket. Khawaja is standing at silly mid on and there is almost a collision between him and Stokes while the single is taken. Oh well, replays showed that Stokes pushed him away!
Length ball, on off. Bairstow looks to work it away but gets the leading edge towards cover.
Who will bowl from the other end? It is Pat Cummins.
Tossed up, on off. Stokes gets forward to block it.
A single as this is pushed to long on.
Flatter, on off. Blocked out.

Great effort by Smith! Tossed up, on off. Bairstow gets low and Smith, who is at first slip charges towards leg slip. The scoop is played and a full-length dive by Smith almost takes the catch. Two runs down to fine leg in the end and that brings up the 100-run stand.
Fuller, around off. Pushed to cover.
Tossed up, on off. Blocked out.
We are back for the final session. Jonny Bairstow and Ben Stokes to continue their innings. Nathan Lyon to roll his fingers...
... Day 3, Session 3 ...

We all thought that Australia will come all guns blazing and repeat the same way as the morning session but things didn't turn out that way. Not many chances were created in this session and credit to the batters to play safe and steady. Lyon was targeted and was driven for runs while the pacers looked a bit off-target. Australia know they are a wicket or two away from opening the gates while England will hope these two continue to play the same way and walk out to bat together on Day 4. But it all depends on what happens in the next couple of hours. Do join us for the final session at 11 am IST (5:30 am GMT).

From 36/4 to 135/4 and counting. This was a brilliant session for England.  They needed Jonny Bairstow and Ben Stokes to stay in the middle and steady the ship and both have done the job exceptionally well as they have stitched a partnership of 99. Both took their time before playing freely and now they are getting boundaries with ease. Stokes brought up his fifty while Bairstow is on the verge to follow him. There was a bizarre moment in the session though when the ball clipped the off pole but the bails stayed on and Stokes survived. Maybe, that was the slice of luck that England needed.

Dot to finish the session and that ends the session! England have not a single wicket and have scored 99 runs! Length ball, down the leg side. Boland slips after bowling that and Stokes leaves it. That will be Tea on Day 3!
On a length, on off. Stokes blocks it out.
Length again, but Stokes leaves this wide one easily.
Too full and too wide. Left alone.
Length ball, way outside off. Stokes takes a step down the track and leaves it.
Fuller ball, outside off. Left alone.
Shorter, outside off. Cut away to point.
Loopy ball, down the leg side. Bairtsow offers his pads to this.
A single as this is pushed to long on.
Loopy ball, around off. Stokes pushes it to cover.
Fuller, on off. Blocked by Stokes again.
Flatter, on off. Blocked out.
Angles it on the pads, this is flicked to deep mid-wicket for a couple. 8 runs coming off the over.
Fuller and on middle, pushed to mid on.
FOUR! Bairstow is dealing in boundaries! A length ball, outside off. Jonny Bairstow guides it through backward point for a boundary.
Almost a yorker, on middle. Bairstow jams it out to square leg for a brace.
Length ball, outside off. Blocked out.
This one skids through, on off. Bairstow gets behind the line to block it out.
Short and outside off. Bairstow cuts it through point and collects three runs. He is eyeing his half-century as well.
FOUR! Races away! Tossed up, on middle. Jonny Bairstow gets on his knee and sweeps it to square leg for a boundary.
On middle, nudged to square leg.
Slightly short, on off. Jonny Bairstow rocks back and blocks it.
Flatter and on middle. Bairstow gets low and defends it towards short leg.
Full and on middle, this is flicked to mid-wicket for a single.
Length and on off. Blocked out.
Full and on off, pushed back to Boland who does well to get low and stop it.
BEATEN! Lovely delivery! A length ball, in the channel of uncertainty! Jonny Bairstow looks for a juicy drive but misses.
Fuller on off, pushed to mid on.

Length ball, on off. Stokes comes down the track and whips it through mid-wicket. The fielder gives a chase and does well to flick it away. Three runs. It also brings up FIFTY for Ben Stokes. Well played. A great knock under pressure by England's southpaw.
A length ball, outside off. Stokes shuffles and blocks it out.
Tossed up, on off, tucked to mid-wicket.
Again width given. Bairstow drives it to point.
Slower, full and on middle. Blocked out.
FOUR! Boundaries flowing! Pre-meditates and paddles this full ball to the fine leg fence.
Full and on middle, Blocked out.
FOUR! Good shot! This is short and way outside off, width on offer and Bairstow lashes on it and the ball races away to the point fence.
Now Stokes comes down and across to block it out.
On a length, on middle, pushed to mid on.
FOUR! Beautifully driven! A full ball, outside off. Stokes leans and drives it through covers for a boundary.
On middle, this is flicked to deep square leg for one more.
Inside edge! A length ball, it lands outside off and nips back in. Stokes gets low to defend but it takes the inside edge to the leg side for a single.
Length and on middle, nudged on the leg side.
Change. The lethal Scott Boland (8-5-8-2) is brought back.
FOUR! Nicely done! Tossed up, on off. This time Jonny Bairstow connects the sweep and finds the square leg fence.
Loopy ball, around off. Jonny drives it past covers for a couple.
Full, on off. Blocked out.
Flatter, on off. Tapped to short leg.
Tossed up, around off. Jonny Bairstow goes for the sweep but gets hit on the pads. There is an appeal for LBW but not given. Impact would have been an issue.
Loopy ball, on off. Worked to short leg.
Full, on the pads. Worked to fine leg for a single.
Back of a length, angling across off. Bairstow leaves it alone.
Short, around off. Left alone.
Fuller, outside off. Driven uppishly but wide of cover for a couple.
On a length, on middle. Bairstow looks to block but gets the inside edge on the pads.
Nicely driven to short cover by Jonny.
Darted on off. Stokes goes back and blocks it.
Full and on the pads. Worked to deep square leg for a couple.
Flatter, on off. Blocked out.
Loopy ball, on off. Stokes comes down the track and drags it past mid-wicket for a couple.
Tossed up, on off. Stokes gets the inside edge past short leg.
Stokes dances down the track and blocks it out. This could be very exciting.
Time for some spin as Nathan Lyon is brought into the attack.
Punched off the back foot past cover for one.
Fuller, around off. Stokes comes forward to block it.
Length, outside off. Left alone.

FOUR! Oh boy! We could be in for an exciting phase of play if Stokes keeps batting like this! Short and on off. He rocks back and pulls it to the mid-wicket fence. That brings up the 50-run stand and these two have looked quite good in the middle.
FOUR! Again! Full, on off. Stokes punches it nicely to the long on fence.
FOUR! Easy pickings. Full and on the pads. Stokes flicks it nicely to the square leg fence.
Full, on off. Pushed back to the bowler.
Nice and full but wide enough to be left alone with ease.
Length ball, on off. Bairstow taps it down on the deck.
Full, on off. Nicely blocked out.
Back of a length, around off. Stokes works it past point for three runs.
Sharp bounce! Short of a length, just outside off. Stokes looks to block it at first but the ball shoots up and goes past the outside edge.

Drinks! A nice period of play for England but they have a long, long way to go still. Aussies know that a couple of wickets should seal the deal for them as the English tail hasn't wagged much in this series.
On the pads, this is tucked away to mid-wicket.
Length ball, around the fourth-stump channel. Jonny Bairstow shoulders arms to it.
Short and way down the leg side. Bairstow lets it through.
Full ball, outside off. Bairstow gets an inside edge as he looks to drive it. The ball goes to the fine leg region and a couple of runs are taken.
Length ball, outside off. Left alone. Carey collects it very low. The pitch is playing it uneven here but the repair work is going on decently for England. Still a long way to go.
Short of a length, around off. Bairstow shoulders arms.
On a length, on off, Blocked out.
A length ball, on middle, some extra pace here from Green. Stokes gets hit on the gloves due to the extra bounce. Drops his bat in pain.
Full and outside off. Left alone by Stokes.
WIDE! Bangs a bouncer on middle. Left alone. Wided.
What a delivery! Angles a full ball, on the pads. Ben Stokes looks to defend but misses and gets hit on the pads.
Touch fuller, on middle. Stokes blocks it back on the deck.
Green serves a short ball, on middle. Stokes sits under it.
On a length, on middle. Blocked out.
Short of a length, on the hips, extra pace too. Bairstow tickles it to fine leg for a couple.
Length ball, angling across. Bairstow leaves it alone.
Very full and on middle, pushed to mid on.
Short and down the leg side. Left alone.
FOUR! Good shot! A full ball, on the pads. Jonny Bairstow flicks it through square leg for a boundary. Runs coming nicely for the visitors now.
Change. Mitchell Starc is back on.
FOUR! Up and over! A length ball, outside off. Stokes smashes it off the toe end of his back but enough to clear mid off. Boundary.
This is full and on off. Stokes is early as he tries to defend and hits it to mid off.
Length and outside off, Left alone.
Full and around off, pushed to covers for a couple.
Full, on middle, pushed to mid on.

NOT OUT! WHAT HAPPENED THERE? Did that hit the stumps? But the bails are intact well. A length ball, this one comes back in sharply with the angle. Stokes shoulders arms to it. The ball goes onto hit the stumps but the bails do not clip off. It did hit hard but still, the bails are in place. Wow! Stokes takes the review but as there was no bat or even a brush of pads there, the on-field decision is overturned. No idea why the umpire raised the finger. The ball was miles away from the pads too.

What has happened? Ben Stokes has taken a review apparently. Wow! The ball hit the stumps but the bails didn't come off. Apparently, the LBW decision has been reviewed. It has missed the pads by a mile! The ball flicked the off pole but the bails have not moved an inch!
Length ball, shaping in and Bairstow slaps it to covers.
Full and outside off. Stokes drives it aerially and towards deep cover for three runs.
Length and on middle. Stokes defend it solidly.
On middle, blocked out on the leg side.
Length ball, outside off. Jonny Bairstow looks to defend it very late and it takes the shoulder of the bat, through the slip cordon and a single is taken.
A length ball, on middle. Defended out.
A length ball, this one jags back in and hits Stokes as he steps down and looks to defend but gets hit high on the pads.
On a length, on off. Stokes steps across and defends it under his eyes.
FOUR! Too straight! Full and on middle. Stokes drives it nicely and wide of mid on for a boundary. England getting along smoothly.
135 clicks! On a length, on middle. Blocked out.
Length ball, outside off. Stokes shuffles way across and pushes it to mid on.
On middle, tucked away to mid-wicket for a single.
Length, just outside off. Stokes leaves it with ease.
Fuller, on off. Blocked out.

DROPPED! Full, on off. Stokes hits it back to the bowler. It comes at nice height to Cummins but he is in his follow through so has less time to react. He gets his hands down but it pops out. He tries to take it again as he is falling down but doesn't hold onto it.
Length, on middle. Stokes taps it to mid-wicket.
Short of a length, outside off, left alone.
Again some issues with the sight screen. This time Ben Stokes is not happy. He backs away as Cummins charges in.
Back of a length, outside off. Left alone.
On a length, on off. Tapped to covers by Bairstow.
Back of a length, outside off. Chopped away but Lyon makes a good stop at point. Wonder when he will get to bowl.
Fuller, on off. Pushed to mid off.
Another halt...now a beach ball pops up out of nowhere on the ground.
Full, on off. Pushed to mid on.
Boland charges in but there is some issue with the sight screen. Jonny Bairstow is not happy with it...
Length, on off. Jonny Bairstow gets forward to block it.
More runs for England! Worked past point for a couple by Jonny.
FOUR! Put away! Short and on middle. Stokes rocks back and pulls it all along the ground to the square leg fence.
Length, around off. It stays a touch low but Stokes blocks it.
FOUR! Thumping shot! Overpitched, on off. Stokes shows the full face of the bat and drives it nicely to the long off fence. A no ball too as Cummins oversteps.
On a length, fifth-stump line. Stokes shoulders arms.
Nicely punched but straight towards short mid off.
This is wider and Stokes makes a leave.
Fuller and angling across off. Stokes is forced to play but the ball goes past the outside edge.
Fuller, around off. Jonny Bairstow gets the outside edge towards gully. Michael Hussey jokes about this being an expensive over for Australia.
First runs in 71 balls and the SCG crowd cheers! Length ball, around off. Stokes gets the outside edge past cover for one.
Length but down the leg side. Stokes misses the glance. He is moving around quite a bit in the crease hoping that Boland will change his length and line.
Length ball, around off. Another easy leave for Stokes.
Nice and full, on off. Blocked out.
Length ball, on the sixth stump. Nicely left alone by Stokes.
Was there some bat on that? Doesn't seem like it. Short of a length, on off. Jonny Bairstow goes for the pull but gets hit on the body. The ball lands short of the dive of Green from gully.
Good-length delivery, right on the off pole. A solid block by Jonny.
Full and down the leg side. Jonny Bairstow misses the flick.
Fuller, on off. Blocked out nicely.
Beaten! That is a peach! On a length, just outside off. Bairstow is beaten as he looks to block.
On a length, outside off. Left alone.
Pat Cummins (7-3-15-0) is back into the attack.
Beaten! On a length, lands outside off. Stokes gets across looking to block it but the ball zips past the outside edge. 10 maidens now.
Almost a run! Stokes works this length ball towards mid on. Both the batters take a step down the track but turn back again.
Boland bowls it full, on off. Blocked out by Stokes.
Stokes takes a step down the track and works it towards mid-wicket.
Back of a length, just outside off. Stokes gets across and blocks it.
On a length, on off. Blocked out.
Who will bowl from the other end? Scott Boland it is.
Full and down the leg side. Left alone and that makes it 9 maidens on the trot.
We are back for the post-Lunch session. Jonny Bairstow will join Ben Stokes in the middle. Cameron Green to bowl the final delivery of his over.
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

Same old, same old for England. Tell you what, there was a period in the first hour where it felt like things could go their way. Hameed was dropped by Carey and Crawley was looking in fine form. But once the first wicket fell, they had nowhere to go. Even Root could not save them this time and they are in big, big trouble. The best-case scenario for them would be to avoid follow-on and pray for some help from the rain gods in this Test. How will they fare in the second session? Join us at 8:40 am IST (3:10 am GMT) to find out.

A dream session for Australia. They bowled probing lines throughout the session and have been rewarded. Mitchell Starc started things off but it was Scott Boland with his 2 wickets who put the session firmly in Australia's bag. Green has taken the late wicket here to put the cherry on the top. They were simply brilliant to bowl 8 maiden overs on the trot is not easy but that pressure has resulted in the last two wickets.
WOW! What a session! Rain dominated the first half but once we got on the field, it has been all about Australia! 4 wickets and they would have a nice meal now.

OUT! TAKEN! This is a trap from Australia! What a session for the hosts! They have both the big wickets before the morning session and Australia will enjoy the Lunch more. A length ball, angling on middle and leg. Malan shuffles and tries to flick it away. It goes more of the inside edge towards leg slip where Usman Khawaja makes a full-length dive forward and takes a sharp catch. That will be Lunch on Day 3.
Commentary.Howout: c Usman Khawaja b Cameron Green

Commentary.Commentary: Again gets hit on the gloves! England can't make a way for themselves! Short of a length, on middle. Malan gets hit on the gloves.
Full ball, outside off. Malan offers no shot to it.
Full and outside off. Left alone.
Length ball, on middle, some steep bounce and Malan gets hit on the gloves as he looks to defend.
JAFFA! Another great over from Boland! Length ball, outside off, a late outswinger. Stokes is squared up as he tries to defend. Eight maiden overs on the trot. Pressure on England piling up.
BEATEN! Lovely bowling! A length ball, coming with the angle. Ben Stokes looks to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Length ball, outside off. Stokes covers his stumps and leaves it alone.
Length ball, on middle and leg. Stokes stays back and defends it out.
Length ball, on middle. Blocked out.
Who will England turn to now? Ben Stokes makes his way to the middle.

OUT! EDGE AND GONE! Australia get the big wicket of Root at the brink of the Lunch break! A duck for Root on today's menu as well. This is on a length and way outside off. The pressure building up over the last few overs gets to Root. He goes for the cut shot but manages an outside edge to second slip where Steven Smith catches it very high. He ain't dropping those. Scott Boland living his life at the moment.
Commentary.Howout: c Steven Smith b Scott Boland

Commentary.Commentary: Make it seven maiden overs in a row! Length ball, outside off. Malan leaves it alone.
Wow. It has been 41 balls since a run was scored.
A length ball, on off. Malan defends it out.
A huge appeal for LBW but height might have saved him! A length ball, this one jags back in sharply and hits Malan on the pads as he looks to flick. Australia opt not to take the review.
Short of a length, slanting outside off. Malan shoulders arms to it.
On a length, outside off. Malan chops it to gully.
Length ball, way outside off. Easy leave.
A length ball, outside off. Root works it on the off side. Six maiden overs in a row.
Fuller ball, on off. Root shuffles and blocks it late.
A length ball, on off. Root guides it to gully and Green does well to dive to his left and stop it.
Length and on off. Defended out.
This one comes with the angle, full and on middle. Root pushes it to mid off.
A full ball, on off. Root defends it to point. Australia will love another wicket here.
A short ball, on off. Malan sways away from the line. Probing lines from Green.
Carey catches this over his head! Length ball, outside off, this one bounces off the crack. Malan leaves it alone.
Fuller ball, outside off. Malan defends it with an angled bat on the off side.
In the air but way short of mid-wicket, Malan didn't time it at all. Short ball, on middle. Malan mistimes his pull towards mid-wicket.
Another leave by Malan. It was way outside off.
A length ball, outside off. Malan leaves it alone.
Joe Root is the new man in and Boland gets a warm welcome as he goes to field at deep backward square leg.

OUT! TIMBER! Both the openers are gone! What a delivery from Scott Boland! This one lands on off and nips back in sharply. Zak Crawley is committed to his drive but gets beaten on the inside edge and the ball disturbs the stumps. Another sloppy start for the openers of England. Boland's dream start to Test cricket continues.
Commentary.Howout: b Scott Boland

Commentary.Commentary: Outside off and Crawley leaves it alone.
This one jags back in, on a length, on middle. Crawley looks to defend but gets hit on the thigh pad.
BEATEN! Right on the money! A length ball, outside off. Zak Crawley looks to defend on the front foot but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Nicely driven but straight to mid off. This was full and on off.
Length and outside off. Left alone.
Maiden over! Another short ball, followed by another leave by Malan. Good carry to Carey.
Short of a length, outside off. Malan stands tall and lets it through to the keeper.
On a length, on off. Blocked out.
Touch fuller, angling outside off. Malan shoulders arms.
Length again, outside off, this one bounces more than expected and Malan misses his cut.
Green starts with a length ball, outside off. It is left alone.
Change from both ends as Cameron Green is on now.
Short of a length, just outside off. Crawley goes back and blocks it.
On a length, around off. Blocked again.
Short of a length, lands outside off and stays a bit low. Zak ends up inside-edging the pull shot on his thigh pad.
Nice and full, on off. Crawley gets forward to block it.
Another one jagging back in but a good leave by Crawley.
Length, lands outside off and comes back in. Left alone.
Scott Boland is into the attack now.
Back of a length, sliding down the leg stumps again. Malan misses the flick.
Short, down the leg side. Left alone.
Short of a length, outside off. Malan goes back and across looking to cut it but misses.
Another nice defence from the crease off Malan's bat.
Length delivery, on off. Malan blocks it.
Lovely cover drive by Malan but straight to short cover.
Clipped down to fine leg for an easy single.
Length, angling across off. Malan leaves it with ease.
Cummins bangs it in, around off. But Malan sways away nicely.
Fuller and straighter. Worked past square leg for a couple. Malan is off the mark.
Length, on off. Malan blocks it towards cover.
Full, on the pads. Malan taps it away.
FOUR! Wow. Where did that come from? A short one and one would have expected him to duck under it. But Crawley pulls it aerially over mid-wicket for a boundary.
Length ball, on the pads. Crawley taps it to the leg side.
Fuller, on middle. Pushed to mid on.

Halt in play. The physio is out to have a check on Zak Crawley. The fingers go numb after this type of hit and he should be fine with some magic spray. We can hear Starc asking Lyon, what did Crawley say the other night! The verbal battle is already on...
Ouch! That rises sharply! Lands on a length, on leg and just takes off. Zak Crawley sets himself up for a nice defence but gets pinged on the gloves. That will sting for sure.
Sharp inswinger now! Length is a bit short and Crawley gets hit on the body as he looks to leave this one.
Length ball, around off. Left alone.
More runs! Zak drives this full ball past mid on now. Boland chases it and puts in the slide. He stops it just before the ropes. Three runs.
FOUR! Lovely stroke. Full, outside off. Zak Crawley plants his front foot forward and drives it through covers for a boundary.
Length ball, around off. Left alone.

Put down! That was a very tough chance though! Length ball, on off. Crawley got the inside edge on the thigh guard. The ball went flying to the right of Harris at short leg. He went to his right, got his hand to it but it popped out.
Length ball, on off. Zak Crawley taps it out.
Shorter, on off. Crawley sways away from the line.
Full again, down the leg side. Malan misses the glance again.
Full, outside off. Malan leaves it.
Full and down the leg side. Malan misses the flick.
Fiery stuff! Back of a length, around off. Malan goes back to block it but the ball rises a bit more than expected. Malan manages to keep it down though.
Dawid Malan walks out at number 3.

OUT! BOWLED! Luck favors Starc this time! He bowls a full one, on off. This one shapes back in a bit. Hameed once again goes for the straight drive without much feet movement. That leaves a big gap between the bat and the pads. That is more than enough for the ball to sneak through and castle the middle stump! Hameed's poor run in the Ashes continues.

Commentary.Commentary: Full and down the leg side. Hameed misses the flick.
Left alone this time as this is quite wide outside off.
Short ball to Crawley, around off. He thinks about pulling it at first but drops his hands in the end.
This comes back in after landing outside off. Zak Crawley nicely covers the stumps and leaves it.
Sliding down the leg side this time and Crawley misses the flick.
Back of a length, just outside off. Crawley looks to block it from the crease but the ball goes past the outside edge.
Length, outside off. Zak covers the stumps and leaves it.
On a length, on middle and leg. Blocked out.
Fuller, landing on middle and tailing back in. Worked towards mid on.
Back of a length, on middle. Blocked out.
FOUR! Nicely played. This will frustrate Starc! Back of a length, just outside off. Hameed nicely guides it past point and gets a boundary.
Length ball, on off. Hameed leaves it on length.

DROPPED! Alex Carey! Could he have left it for Warner to catch it? That was going straight towards Warner at first slip! Length ball, angling across off. Haseeb Hameed looks to block it from the crease. The ball takes the outside edge and flies away. Carey dives full length to his right and gets his glove to it but the ball doesn't stick. It would have gone straight to Warner had Carey not gone for that.
Back of a length, around off. Blocked out with ease.
Well bowled! This shapes away! On a length, just outside off. Zak Crawley is forced to play and he looks to block it from the crease. The ball shapes away just enough to beat the outside edge.
Too high. Lands on a length, outside off and comes back in. Zak Crawley gets hit on the thigh while looking to block.
Fuller ball, on the fourth stump. Crawley gets on top of the ball and blocks it.
On a length, outside off. Left alone this time.
Top shot! Full, on off. Driven nicely past mid off by Zak Crawley. Marnus Labuschagne gives it the chase and dives to stop the ball. But given the long boundaries at the SCG, the batters run four!
Who will bowl from the other end? It is Pat Cummins with three slips and a gully.
Starc bowls a short one, around off. Left alone again.
Ooh! Length ball, lands on off and angles away. The ball goes just past the off pole as Hameed leaves it.
First runs of the day. Short and down the leg side. Zak Crawley toe-ends the pull shot. It goes past the keeper and down to fine leg for one.
A lot wide as Starc wants Crawley to drive this but the batter leaves it.
Nice and full, around off. Crawley puts in a nice stride to block it.
Starc steams in with the SCG crowd cheering him up. He serves a full ball, around off. Zak Crawley pushes it towards mid on.
After the delayed start, we are all set for action. England openers will resume their innings. Here is Mitchell Starc to Zak Crawley...

So here are the revised play parameters for the day. A minimum of 73 overs to be bowled. Lunch break will be taken at 8 am IST (2:30 am GMT) and the final session will start at 11 am IST (5:30 am GMT). Terms and conditions apply. Terms and conditions being rain.

UPDATE 5:52 am IST (12:22 am GMT) - Good news folks! The covers are coming off. The conditions are still overcast and the groundstaff are working hard to clear the ground. We still wait for any official comment as to when we can have a resumption. Stay tuned. Okay, play will start at 6:40 am IST (1:10 am GMT).

A stunning Test! We witnessed a brilliant comeback by South Africa at the Wanderers. At the end of Day 3, the equation was simple. The hosts needed 122 runs to win and India needed 8 wickets. What was supposed to be an epic showdown in the first session on Day 4 turned into a dull affair. The heavens decided to open up as it was pouring down steadily. Two sessions were washed out and given that the forecast for Day 5 wasn't that great, everyone was getting frustrated. After all, what had been a brilliant game deserved a result. But with some good luck, we finally resumed the final session with plenty of cloud cover. It was expected that the Indian pacers would trouble the batters and to be honest, they did get some help from the pitch. But the aggressive intent of the South African batters put the bowlers under pressure. They went a bit overboard at times and on more than one occasion, bouncers went over Rishabh Pant and into the fence. The South African batters were brilliant though. Riding on a bit of luck, they never let India get back in the game. Dean Elgar was sensational with his 96* and led his team to series leveling victory. It was the first time that India were beaten by South Africa at the Wanderers and the final Test in Cape Town promises to be an epic battle between these two sides.

UPDATE 4:56 am IST (11:26 pm GMT, previous day) - It is still pouring at the SCG and we wait for some positive news. The whole ground is covered now and looks like the first session could be washed off if it continues like this. Let us hope that the rain stops and we can resume the play. Stay tuned.

World Cup squad declared! Meanwhile, India declared their squad for the upcoming Women's World Cup to be played in New Zealand. Mithali Raj will lead the team but there have been a couple of talking points already. Jemimah Rodrigues, who has been in quite good form in franchise cricket and Shikha Pandey, have been left out of the squad. The BCCI hasn't provided any official statement as to why they were excluded from the squad but there have been unconfirmed reports that both the players were dropped due to their poor run in the ODI format in the recent past.

UPDATE 4:15 am IST (10:45 pm GMT, previous day) - Ugggh. I hate to be the bearer of bad(ish) news. Currently reading reports that there is a slight drizzle at the SCG at this point in time and the covers are in place now. But hopefully, as we saw during the first session on Day 2, these rain spells could be short. But for now, the start has been officially delayed.

Both the teams made one change before this match and both of them made a big impact. Usman Khawaja scored a brilliant century, thanks to a dropped catch by Root and some valuable runs from tail-enders helped Australia to declare on 416-8. Stuart Broad with a five-for was the only positive for the visitors. To add to England’s woes, the pitch tends to be uneven as the match progresses and England have a tough job ahead. Things will pretty much rely on how the openers play out the first session. Stay tuned for further updates and also pray that the rain stays away.

Hello and a warm welcome to the third day of this fourth Test match between Australia and England. The visitors ended the second day unhurt, luckily as Zak Crawley edged one but eventually it was called a no ball. Now they will look to make the most of it and start the morning session positively.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

Not too much data to gather but England have looked assured in their short stay. Of course, not much will matter when they come out on Friday morning, but to start a day with all 10 wickets in hand, gives you a good feeling. Australia would have liked a wicket before Stumps but their main aim would be try and bowl out England on Day 3. Batting is difficult but the pitch does not have demons as such. If the batters apply themselves, they can get runs on what is called the moving day of a Test match. However, they need to be wary of Nathan Lyon with the ball already turning on Day 2. Join us then, on Friday, 7th January, 2022, well before 4.30 am IST (2300 GMT, previous day) for all the buildup before the first ball on Day 3. In the meanwhile, you can catch all the cricketing action from the second South Africa-India Test and the Big Bash League. ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

Australia's day, by and far. They started the day with a bit of uncertainty, with two relatively new batsmen in Khawaja and Smith. But England eased all their nerves, dishing them far too many easy deliveries and in almost next to no time, the Aussies were up and running. They made England toil and that showed, with England's skipper Joe Root shelling an easy catch of Usman Khawaja on 28, off Jack Leach. And he went onto score 137. Broad's 5-fer was the only soft corner in a rough day, but they would have loved every bowler's strike rate to be a bit better.

England would be mighty relieved that they have seen off a nervy 20 minutes of play. They have hardly had any luck in this series and certainly derserve some slice of fortune. Zak Crawley had mentioned about being brave and not fearing the Aussie bowlers and that reprieve by Starc might just turn a corner for him and his team. It always feels good to start a day with all 10 wickets in hand and the tourists would be confident that they can show some fight, come Friday.

Hameed survives and that will be it for Day 2! Pat Cummins ends a probing spell with a length ball, angled into middle and leg. Hameed hangs back and just about manages to keep it out. With a bit of luck and perseverance, England do not lose any wickets.

Close but not close enough. Cummins goes fuller this time and catches Hameed on the crease. Hameed looks to go back and play it late with soft hands but gets an outside edge which goes towards the gully region.

Well, that one swung a mile once again. Cummins goes wide of the crease and bowls an inswinger which pitches around the off pole. The ball just nips in sharply off the surface but Hameed gets right behind the line to block it out.
Good-length ball, around off and shaping in a bit. Haseeb Hameed hops on the back foot and plays it late.
Pat Cummins angles this one into middle stump but Hameed defends it out. His heart must be pounding real hard right now.
Cummins is charging in here. A length ball, outside off and the ball zips through. Haseeb Hameed makes the leave. 5 more to go!
Nice and full, on off. Equally nice defence by Zak Crawley.
On a length, on off. Blocked out.
Full and on the pads. Zak Crawley clips it to deep square leg for a couple.

NO BALL! Oh no! The celebrations in the Aussie camp are halted. Just as Starc was looking a bit under par with his bowling, he bowls an absolute ripper. The ball is delivered on a good length, just around the off pole and the batter has to play at it. The ball angles across a bit and bounces a bit extra as well. Zak Crawley gets the faintest of outside edges and the ball flies towards first slip. David Warner takes a sharp catch around his chest and Crawley seems to be out on a duck yet again. But hold on, the umpires check for the front foot and Starc doesn't have anything behind the line. It looks very close though as the foot is very close to the line when it makes an impact but the TV umpire feels that it is a no ball. Crawley walks back to the middle and the Aussies cannot believe it.
Good-length ball, around the fifth stump. Zak Crawley shoulders arms. Starc looks like he is lacking a bit of rhythm.
A length ball, down the leg side. Crawley misses the flick.
Back of a length, outside off and left alone.
Another inswinger, this time around middle. Hameed looks to flick but the ball just flies after pitching and goes down the leg side. Good take from Carey to his left.

Ooh! That one swung late and swung a long way back in. Cummins keeps probing outside the off stump and finally goes for the big in-dipper. Hameed leaves it as it is a fair bit outside off but the ball swings in late and goes past the off stump.
Cummins looks to bring the ball back in but bowls this one wide of off stump. Hameed makes yet another leave.
Back of a length, outside off stump. Hameed lets it through to the keeper.
Length again, 141 kph and slanting down the leg side. Hameed looks to defend it off the back foot but gets beaten.
'Gardening' is the term used by Michael Vaughan while referring to the batters tapping the pitch in between balls to make sure that they face as few overs as possible here.

Edged but safe! Good-length ball, on off. Haseeb Hameed goes backward and looks to push at it but does so with hard hands. The ball goes off the outside edge and luckily for Hameed, falls short of Cameron Green at gully.
Shorter in length, around off and this one angles across the batter. Crawley leaves it alone.

FOUR LEG BYES! Mitchell Starc looks to attack the pads but gets it a bit too straight. Zak Crawley looks to flick but misses. The ball goes off the pads and flies past the diving keeper and into the fine leg fence.
Starc goes fuller, around middle. Crawley defends it off the front foot.
Mark Wood is padded up but the visitors would hope that he does not have to bat for a long, long time.
Angled across the right-hander and pitches just around off. Crawley reads it off the hand and makes an assured leave.
A length ball, on off. Hameed plays it with soft hands towards covers and sets off for a quick single. Good running.
Starc pitches it up, around off and looks to bring the ball back into the right-hander. Hameed stays solid in defense.
Mitchell Starc to steam in from the other end.

FOUR BYES! My word! That one took off like an airplane! This one is delivered on a good length, just around the off pole. Zak Crawley makes a leave but the ball just shoots up after pitching and flies over the keeper's head for a boundary. No chance that Carey was getting to that one.

Ooh! That one came back in a fair bit. On a length, around 139 kph and just outside off. Zak Crawley puts out a stride and looks to leave but the ball nips back in sharply off the surface and raps Crawley on the pads. It's a bit too high and hence no appeal.
Length this time, on top of off. Zak Crawley plays it late and defends it under his eyeline.
Cummins pitches it a bit further up but it's well outside off. Crawley makes an easy leave.
England are off the mark. Cummins goes full, trying to attack the pads. Hameed clips it nicely through mid-wicket. His partner Zak Crawley wants two but Hameed isn't interested. Just a single then.

Pat Cummins steams in and gets the ball moving right away. On a good length, in that corridor of uncertainty. The ball shapes away after pitching. Haseeb Hameed is caught in two minds but eventually leaves it alone.

45 minutes. That is what Australia have got. Can they take a wicket or two? Roughly 10-11 overs. 45 minutes. That is what England have got too. Can they see off this period and go to Stumps unbeaten? Haseeb Hameed and Zak Crawley walk out once again to do what is possibly still the toughest job in cricket - opening the innings. It will be Mitchell Starc, no doubt, to start the proceedings. Haseeb Hameed has put his hand up to face the first ball. Three slips, a gully and a man at short leg catching. Here we go... Let's play!
... FINAL INNINGS ...

Mitchell Starc - swing. Pat Cummins - accuracy. Scott Boland - Hard length. Nathan Lyon - turn and bounce. Cameron Green - bounce. This is the bowling attack that England have to face. It looks daunting but this is where mental courage comes into play. They need to play in small buckets - see off the day today without any loss and then grind it out tomorrow with a little bit of hope from the weather.

A bizarre batting display by Australia but something which they would have wanted. The middle order fired from a tricky position and pushed England out of the match. England exploited bounce and carry through Wood while Leach extracted some turn. The pitch looks a bit flat but it is dry and there are signs of inconsistent bounce. Those cracks might widen up tomorrow, especially if the sun bakes down on it.

Ohh... that is so cruel from Pat Cummins! This is what Jack Leach would be saying. Pat Cummins calls his players back, denying Leach a possible hattrick and a 5-fer. AUSTRALIA DECLARE WITH A TARGET OF 388 FOR ENGLAND. Do not think that this has got anything with the score, it is just that the hosts do not want to give any moment of joy to the tourists. It has been another tough outing. But for now, the entire SCG is on its feet. This is his arena. Take a bow, Usman Khawaja. To come back in this fashion, scoring twin centuries in a Test gets out the statement from the great man, Shane Warne, on air - 'HE IS UNDROPPABLE.' He adds that Cummins was the new man in and he certainly did not want to face the hat-trick ball, so just declared. Ha ha! Never minces his words, does he, the great Shane.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Just as Alex Carey started to walk off, Cummins signaled his batters to come back. A flatter ball, angling into the left-hander, on middle. Alex Carey looks to sweep but gets an inside edge onto the pads. The ball lobs and goes to Ollie Pope who dives to his right and does well to hold onto it. England appeal but the umpire is not yet convinced and tells them to wait but Carey started to walk off and Australia declare their innings and now England need 388 runs to win. Usman Khawaja stays unbeaten on 101.
Commentary.Howout: c sub Ollie Pope b Jack Leach

Commentary.Commentary: Looks like Australia are not in a mood to declare yet as Khawaja is still standing in the middle. Who will join him? It is Alex Carey.

OUT! TAKEN! A fine innings from Cameron Green comes to an end. Tossed up, on middle. Green got an inside edge on the previous delivery as he tried to sweep and this time gets a top edge. High in the air and towards short fine leg where Joe Root runs forward and takes it.
Commentary.Howout: c Joe Root b Jack Leach

Commentary.Commentary: Tossed up, on middle. Green looks to sweep it but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
SIX! Cameron Green fancying a century now? A full ball, on middle. Green skips down and tonks it over long on for a biggie.
Tossed up, on off. Blocked out.
On a length, on off. 137 clicks! Usman Khawaja hops and taps it to cover.
Touch fuller, on off. Khawaja defends it out.
Slower, short ball, on middle, pulled away to mid-wicket.
A short ball, drifting down the leg side. Khawaja sits under it.
Full ball, outside off, Khawaja drives it nicely but straight to point.
Fuller and on middle, Green shuffles and pushes it to mid on for a quick single.

DRINKS BREAK. Well... is anyone getting the feeling that there is a slight window of opportunity open for Cameron Green to get his hundred? Because Australia have got more than enough. The lead reads 380 and there are 19 overs scheduled tonight, plus another 98 tomorrow. Deduct 2 for innings break, which means 115 overs and the starting required rate is already close to 3.5. It is indeed about time and Cummins does not want more than say, 10 overs perhaps tonight, so that his bowlers are fresh tomorrow and the ball is still new. Which means - 9 overs. Can Green do a Khawaja by going berserk? Can Uzzie do a Cam by playing second fiddle? And can England eke out cheap wicket (s) in the process? Clearly, no one trusts the weather forecast any more.
Short ball, on middle, Green mistimes his pull to long on for a single.
FOUR! Freebie! A full toss, on middle. Cameron Green thumps it to square leg for a boundary.
Shorter and on off. Green punches off the back foot to covers.
Full ball again, Usman Khawaja works it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Full and on off. Kept out.

CENTURY for Usman Khawaja! Take a bow! What a fantastic innings from him. A short ball, on middle, this is pulled away to deep mid-wicket for a couple of runs. Whole of the SCG is on their feet as they applaud this incredible effort. Back-to-back centuries for him, precisely.
Review taken! Root takes the review for LBW! HotSpot shows no bat there. UltraEdge confirms the same. Ball Tracker shows wickets missing and England lose their review.

NOT OUT! That was going down with the angle and Khawaja survives! Length ball, angling on middle and leg. Usman Khawaja misses and gets hit on the pads. An appeal for LBW but not given. An optimistic review from England but it does not turn out in their favour as the Ball Tracker shows wickets were missing.
A low full toss, way outside off. Usman Khawaja slashes at it but misses. Nervous 90s for Usman Khawaja!
Left alone! A full ball, very full and way outside off. Khawaja lets it through to the keeper.
Full ball, on middle, this is flicked to the right of mid on for a single. Usman Khawaja on 98.
Length ball, outside off. Green slaps it to point.
FOUR! Short of a length, outside off. Green gets on his toes and powers it through covers for a boundary.
Now some boos for Cameron Green as he retains the strike. SCG are lively today! Flatter and on middle, flicked to square leg for a single.
Two is the call but settles with a single, On the pads, this is flicked to deep square leg for one.
Tossed up, on middle. Green works it to point and gives the strike back to Khawaja.
On middle, this is hit to mid-wicket for a single.
The SCG cheers as Usman Khawaja comes back on the strike! Fuller ball, outside off, pushed to long off for a single.
Slower, short ball, outside off, it stays low and Green punches it to cover.
Change. Dawid Malan to bowl now as he relaces Root.
Length ball, on middle, Green flicks it to deep square leg and retains the strike.
Bangs a short ball, on off. Green sways away from it.

RECORD ALERT! This is the highest aggregate for Usman Khawaja in a Test match - going past his 226 (85 and 141) against Pakistan in Dubai in 2018. Well, he has NEVER scored twin centuries in a Test so far. Could this be the first instance?
Fuller ball, on middle, tucked to mid-wicket.
Wood comes around the wicket and bowls a length ball, on off. Blocked out.
Short of a length, outside off. Green punches it to point.
Fuller and outside off, pushed softly to mid off for a single.
Length ball, outside off, pushed to deep cover for a single. Usman Khawaja moves to 95 now. One hit away from reaching the triple-digit score.
Darted on the pads, this is flicked to deep square leg for a single. 150 of the partnership between these two. Just brilliant.
An innings full of innovation! Full ball, on middle. Khawaja reverse sweeps it to deep point for a single.
SIX! Usman Khawaja into the 90s. Full ball now, outside off. Usman Khawaja gets low and tonks it well over mid-wicket for a maximum.
Australia lead by 350 runs now! Full again, drilled down to long on for a single.
Fuller, flighted, on middle. Blocked out on the front foot.
Around off, Khawaja defends it. Australia's lead one short of 350.
Length ball, outside off. Usman Khawaja makes room and tries to guide it down but misses.
Length ball, outside off. Green punches it to deep cover for a single.
Short of a length, angling outside off, it also shoots off the deck. Green has a poke at it but misses. A lose shot after some time from Green. But no damage done.
Length and on off. Green blocks it out.
FOUR! FIFTY for Cameron Green! A well, composed innings from him. He was anxious early on but has settled nicely! Short ball, on middle, pulled away to mid-wicket for a boundary.
On middle. Defended out by Green.
A full ball, angling on middle and leg. Usman Khawaja looks to play the reverse sweep again but misses it completely. An appeal for LBW but not given. There was an inside edge.
On the pads, flicked to mid-wicket for a single.
Full ball, outside off, drilled down to long off for a single.
FOUR! Nicely played! A full ball, on middle. Usman Khawaja reverse hits it well and over point for a boundary.
Full and outside off. Left alone.
Fuller and on middle, flicked through mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Short of a length, angling down. Green ducks but it doesn't bounce much and hits Green on his back.
Full and outside off. Green drives it and beats the diving cover fielder and collects a brace.
Length and on off. Green blocks it towards cover.
Fuller and outside off. Defended out.
FOUR! Welcome to the attack says Green! Short in length, on middle. Green pulls it to the mid-wicket fence.
Mark Wood is back into the attack now.
Darted on the pads and this is flicked to deep square leg for a single.
Full and on the pads, Defended out.
Flatter and on middle. Blocked out.
Around off. Kept out.
Usman Khawaja is making batting look so easy right now! A full ball, on middle. He gets into the position quickly as he paddles it to fine leg for three runs.
FOUR! Driven and beats the man in the deep as well! Khawaja is eyeing back-to-back centuries now! A full ball, outside off. Usman Khawaja drives it hard and through covers for a boundary.
200 up for Australia! Tossed up, on middle. Usman Khawaja works it to deep square leg for a single.
On middle, Blocked out.
Fuller again, on middle. Usman Khawaja reverse sweeps it to deep point for a couple of single.
Misfield and a single! A full ball, on middle. Green paddles it towards square leg. The ball bounces right in front of the fielder and he fumbles to collect it. A single.
Fuller and outside off, pushed through covers for a single.
Leg bye! Angles it on the pads. Green misses his flick and gets rapped on the pads. A leg bye as it rolls to fine leg.
One guesses the message is pretty clear from Pat to Uzzie - Get your century as quickly as you can. You have roughly 30 more minutes. Which is why, we are seeing Khawaja getting more expansive.
Better from Root! Gives flight to it and serves it way outside off. Usman Khawaja looks to drive but gets an outside edge wide of first slip.
FOUR! Freebie and it is dispatched! A short ball, asking to be hit and Usman Khawaja pulls it towards deep square leg for a boundary.
Root continues to give width outside off, this is driven to point.
Slower through the air and outside off. Green punches off the back foot to deep point. One.
Driven again by Khawaja through covers for a single.
Full and way outside off, driven nicely but straight to short cover.
Full again and this is worked to square leg for a single.
SIX! Off the middle! This was full and outside off. Usman Khawaja gets on his knee and slog-sweeps it over mid-wicket for a biggie. 100-run partnership between these two. Australia lead by 309 runs.
Outside off. Khawaja skips down and bunts it to mid-wicket.
Shorter, slower and outside off. Green punches it to deep cover for an easy single.
Waits for this full ball and Green tucks it through square leg for a couple.
On middle, this is hit back to the bowler.
Full and on middle. Usman Khawaja reverse sweeps it but finds backward point.
Fuller ball, on off. Khawaja works it to mid-wicket.
This is way outside off. Khawaja guides it to point.
Flighted ball, on middle. Green drills it to long on for a single.
A single as this is pushed to long off.
Tossed up, on middle. Usman Khawaja mistimes his paddle to the leg side and the slip fielder runs across and dives to stop it.
A loopy ball, on middle. Green gets low and on the front foot to defend this out.
Fuller and angling on the pads, this is flicked to deep square leg for a single.
This is hit to mid-wicket.
Fuller ball, on middle. Usman Khawaja reverse sweeps it nicely towards deep point for a couple.
Sharp turn for both the spinners. On middle, turning in, Khawaja tucks it towards square leg.
Fuller and on off. Khawaja works it to mid-wicket.
A short ball but way down the leg side. Green misses his pull.
Targets the stumps, pushed to the leg side.
Sharp turn! Flatter, outside off, this one turns back in sharply. Green waits and looks to guide it down but in the end leaves it alone.
Darted on the pads, Green turns it to square leg.
Short, outside off, cut away to deep point for a single.
Fuller and on middle, eased down to long on for a single.
A length ball, on middle. Usman Khawaja gets hit on the gloves as he looks to block it.
FOUR! Placement! A length ball, outside off. Usman Khawaja uses his crease and opens the bat face to steer it to third man for a boundary.
Length and on middle, pushed back to the bowler.
FOUR! FIFTY for Usman Khawaja! What a comeback this is! Takes all the applause from the pavilion and the SCG! Pitches it up, outside off. Khawaja drives it firmly through covers for a boundary.
Short ball, on off. Usman Khawaja blocks by getting on top of it.
Swing and a miss! A full ball, outside off, Usman Khawaja tries to cut but the ball was way closer than he thought and ends up missing it. It didn't even bounce much.

BREAKING NEWS - Ahh well. As if things were not already bad. 2021 T20 World Cup hero, Matthew Wade, the charismatic skipper of Hobart Hurricanes, has PULLED OUT OF THE BBL, citing personal reasons. The Hurricanes' management is hopeful of having him back soon though. Hurricanes play the Brisbane Heat later tonight. Correction. Wade-less Hurricanes play player-less Heat later tonight.
Again on the pads. Khawaja dances down and bunts it to square leg for a single.
Darted on the pads, this is flicked on the leg side.
FOUR! First signs of aggression from Khawaja! Full and on middle. He skips down and flicks it to mid-wicket for a boundary.
A single as this is drilled down to mid on.
Shorter ball now and Green hits it to covers.
Fuller ball, on off, eased down to mid off.
Length ball, on off. Defended out.
Is Green run out? The replay shows that he was inside his crease.

NOT OUT! A length ball, way outside off. Green punches it wide of covers and looks for a quick single. The fielder there, dives and scores a direct hit at the bowler's end. The replay shows Green was inside his crease.
Angles a full ball, on middle. Green nudges it to mid-wicket.
Shorter in length, on middle, pulled away nicely wide of deep square leg for one run.
Short of a length, on off. Khawaja hops and defends it.
FOUR! Well wide of the keeper! A length ball, angling way down the leg side. Usman Khawaja tickles it past the diving keeper and it runs away to the fine leg fence.
Who will bowl from the other end? It is Stuart Broad.
A loopy ball, on off, this is pushed back to the bowler.
Flatter and on middle. Blocked out.

And, we end this Lunch segment with Big Bash news. Not for the first time this season, the BBL fixtures have been revised again. Considering that 6 teams out of 8 have been affected by Covid, Cricket Australia has decided to shift all the teams to Melbourne, with a rejigged schedule announced for the coming week. Majority of the matches are slated to be played in Victoria. 7 out of the 11 games in this week will be played here. Some key games will still be played interstate, with teams to fly in and out on charter flights. Those interstate games are the Sydney Derby at the SCG on 15th January, 2022 and the Brisbane Heat-Adelaide Strikers clash at the 'Gabba on 12th January. While Victoria has today recorded more than 83,000 active cases of COVID-19, having all teams based in one city will allow organisers to swap the order of games at the last minute if required, as was done on the Gold Coast on Tuesday after the outbreak in the Heat camp. In a statement, the League said confirmation of the remaining regular season matches - including the postponed Heat-Sixers clash from January 5 - should be expected in the coming days.

And now, news from Australia. Cricket followers in this country will definitely be watching the Ashes, but they will also be eyeing how Will Pucovski performs for Melbourne club over the weekend. One of the most promising players for the future, Pucovski has been hit by injuries more often than not, but curiously, his injuries mostly are a result of concussion (10 times that we know of, at least!). While this takes a big toll on mental health, imagine what would be his case when greats like Shane Warne on air loudly call out that they are not sure whether Pucovski can survive in international cricket. However, the 23-year old is focussing on cricket and wants to make a comeback, targetting Australia's tour to Pakistan in March 2022. Will's latest injury was a shoulder one. He will be playing his first game in almost a year.

Meanwhile, former great Desmond Haynes has replaced Roger Harper as the lead selector for West Indies cricket. Ramnaresh Sarwan too, would be a part of the panel, having stepped down as Guyana Cricket Board chairman, to avoid any conflict of interest. Haynes has signed a contract until June 2024, which sees two T20 World Cups and one 50-over World Cup. Haynes was shortlisted for the 2019 marquee event too, but was eventually beaten by Phil Simmons to the role.

In other international news, in what comes as a fresh breath of air, Sri Lankan cricket has lifted the international bans on Danushka Gunathilaka, Kusal Mendis and Niroshan Dickwella, with less than 6 months into the suspension period. However, they have also cautioned the trio that if it ends in a disciplinary breach again within the next two years, the remainder of the suspension would also kick in. This decision has been taken considering a request made by the trio. Originally, they were given complete bans, which included domestic cricket as well but a request saw them play the Lanka Premier League and now, in all likelihood, will see them feature for Sri Lanka again. In fact, an SLC media release stated - 'Based on such request, Sri Lanka Cricket obtained a report from the doctor appointed by SLC to provide counselling for the three players during their period of suspension.' The ban was enforced during Sri Lanka's tour of England in 2021, when the trio was found breaching bio-bubble protocols. Sri Lanka begin their next assignment which would be an ODI series against Zimbabwe at home, from January 16, 2022.

INTERNATIONAL CRICKET UPDATES - Well, there cannot be any match these days without any mention of Covid. Ireland are due to play the West Indies in the Caribbean in the first of 3 ODIs today, at Jamaica. The tour also features a T20I. This is actually a part of Ireland's tour of America, which started with playing against the United States first, followed by the Caribbean tour. However, plenty of covid cases meant that the ODIs against the USA were scrapped off. And now, from there on, Ireland have been forced to leave out PAUL STIRLING - one of their mainstays in batting - along with SHANE GETKATE - after both players tested positive for the virus. Let's hope there are no more cases and this tour takes place at scheduled. The first ball will be bowled at 8 pm IST (1430 GMT) but as you know, the buildup will begin well in advance. So do tune in early.

Australia are positive. They have always been. If England can be positive, it makes the match so much worth viewing. We get a contest. Rather than relying on the weather, how about trying to bowl Australia out - say under 150 or something? At least give yourselves a chance to win the game, than trying to escape from jail with a draw? Let's hope the players have a good lunch and give us some entertaining cricket after the break. The first ball will be bowled at 7.40 am IST (0210 GMT).

One can understand the mental state of England, but sorry to say, this is a Test match. You have always got to be positive and try to win, even if the odds are against you. Yes, there is less likelihood of England surviving with the bat if they are to play this strong Aussie attack for more than two sessions but if you mentally give up, you will never achieve anything. India would have never won the series 2-1 Down Under last year if they had given up because there was no Kohli and with every passing Test, players were getting injured. More recently, South Africa would have never won at Johannesburg if they had just succumbed to the pressure created by India.

In spite of the umbrella on the boundary, Australia are ticking along at almost 3.5 runs an over. Their lead has swelled up to 188 and another 100 runs would keep them in good stead. England are a bowler down with Ben Stokes not looking like he will bowl. However, both teams will have an eye on the weather. As per the forecast, thunderstorms are due to visit the SCG somewhere close to Tea time today and the hosts would want to get their lead to 200 by then. The visitors, well, will hope that they get a good break with the thunderstorms and get to bat as few overs as possible.

Imagine this - a spinner is introduced in the 10th over of the innings and even before he bowls his first ball, we have a sweeper cover in place. And as the session wore on, we could see a deep mid-wicket, deep cover, deep point, third man and fine leg for almost everyone. Clearly, England are only trying to stop the boundaries and defensive fields can never make up for good cricket.
